1
00:00:14,014 --> 00:00:15,849
PREVIOUSLY

2
00:00:15,915 --> 00:00:17,450
Please welcome
Choi Yang-rak, Paeng Hyun-sook,

3
00:00:17,517 --> 00:00:19,052
and Park Myung-soo!

4
00:00:19,119 --> 00:00:21,554
-It's the return match special.
-A day of revenge.

5
00:00:21,621 --> 00:00:23,056
APPLICANTS:
BAE GYEONG-JUN, FABRI

6
00:00:23,123 --> 00:00:24,691
Come on out.

7
00:00:24,758 --> 00:00:27,093
-He's a fake Italian.
-A fake Italian?

8
00:00:28,194 --> 00:00:29,229
Revenge.

9
00:00:29,295 --> 00:00:30,864
I'll fight him here and win.

10
00:00:30,930 --> 00:00:34,100
<i>This is the first round</i>
<i>of the return match special.</i>

11
00:00:34,167 --> 00:00:37,070
<i>I'll get my revenge with dim sum</i>
<i>against the Queen of Dim Sum.</i>

12
00:00:37,137 --> 00:00:38,271
A HEAD-ON FIGHT!

13
00:00:38,338 --> 00:00:40,006
<i>I should teach her a lesson.</i>

14
00:00:40,073 --> 00:00:41,574
It's 120 out of 100.

15
00:00:41,641 --> 00:00:42,642
The winner is?

16
00:00:42,709 --> 00:00:44,411
CHEF JUNG JI-SUN WINS

17
00:00:44,477 --> 00:00:46,613
-Chef Ji-sun wins.
-Oh, no.

18
00:00:46,679 --> 00:00:48,915
The second return match.

19
00:00:48,982 --> 00:00:51,518
<i>He's here to ram into Hyun-suk.</i>

20
00:00:51,584 --> 00:00:53,486
What are you doing?
Aren't you going to cook?

21
00:00:53,553 --> 00:00:55,522
-The blender!
-The blender!

22
00:00:55,588 --> 00:00:57,891
-You can do it, Gyeong-jun!
-What's he doing?

23
00:00:57,957 --> 00:01:00,393
-It smells smoky.
-Is that so?

24
00:01:00,960 --> 00:01:02,429
CHEF BAE GYEONG-JUN WINS

25
00:01:02,495 --> 00:01:06,032
Bae Gyeong-jun!
Hyun-sook chose Gyeong-jun.

26
00:01:06,099 --> 00:01:09,636
-He got his revenge.
-Yes. Gyeong-jun!

27
00:01:09,702 --> 00:01:11,638
You're watching <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>.

28
00:01:11,704 --> 00:01:13,973
We're here with the first comedian couple,
Hyun-sook and Yang-rak,

29
00:01:14,040 --> 00:01:17,444
as well as the big star comedian,
Myung-soo.

30
00:01:17,510 --> 00:01:19,846
Myung-soo has recently claimed
that this period was

31
00:01:19,913 --> 00:01:22,549
-his 14th glory days.
-That's right.

32
00:01:22,615 --> 00:01:24,818
-It's not the second one?
-I've seen many glory days.

33
00:01:24,884 --> 00:01:26,653
-You've reached the 14th one.
-Yes.

34
00:01:26,719 --> 00:01:29,255
-Your YouTube channel took off.
-Yes, it's doing well.

35
00:01:29,322 --> 00:01:33,059
Videos of my reviews usually do the best.

36
00:01:33,126 --> 00:01:35,595
<i>People simply love</i>
<i>seeing videos of me eating something.</i>

37
00:01:35,662 --> 00:01:39,199
<i>When convenience stores launch</i>
<i>new product lines,</i>

38
00:01:39,265 --> 00:01:42,435
<i>I review them on another channel</i>
<i>my agency runs.</i>

39
00:01:42,502 --> 00:01:43,970
It's sweet. It's too sweet.

40
00:01:44,037 --> 00:01:45,638
It's too spicy and bitter.

41
00:01:45,705 --> 00:01:47,841
I don't think it's for me. I'm sorry.

42
00:01:47,907 --> 00:01:50,510
<i>All I do is taste their food. That's all.</i>

43
00:01:50,577 --> 00:01:52,645
That's why
you all need to be careful today.

44
00:01:52,712 --> 00:01:54,481
I'm going to bluntly say

45
00:01:54,547 --> 00:01:56,683
what it's like as it is.

46
00:01:56,749 --> 00:01:59,619
You may end up feeling down
and hitting your rock bottom.

47
00:01:59,686 --> 00:02:01,087
-So brace yourselves.
-He's scary.

48
00:02:01,154 --> 00:02:02,989
I'm honestly not scared of anything.

49
00:02:03,056 --> 00:02:05,425
I'll be blunt.
If it's awful, I'll say it's awful.

50
00:02:05,492 --> 00:02:07,060
-He'll be blunt.
-That's scary.

51
00:02:07,127 --> 00:02:10,363
Show me everything you've got.
Do you understand?

52
00:02:10,430 --> 00:02:12,432
-Everything we've got?
-I'm not here to make you laugh.

53
00:02:12,499 --> 00:02:15,668
-I'm only here to review your food.
-Really?

54
00:02:15,735 --> 00:02:18,171
My reviews always rake in
at least a million views.

55
00:02:18,238 --> 00:02:19,939
I'm looking at you four right now.

56
00:02:20,006 --> 00:02:21,407
DON'T YOU DARE MAKE IT TASTE BAD

57
00:02:21,474 --> 00:02:22,942
I'm watching all of you

58
00:02:23,009 --> 00:02:25,378
-who don't seem confident.
-Are you saying you'll drop us?

59
00:02:25,445 --> 00:02:27,714
-But if you are…
-Yes?

60
00:02:27,780 --> 00:02:31,584
…overly blunt and honest with the chefs,

61
00:02:31,651 --> 00:02:34,053
-they'll be hurt.
-That's not my business.

62
00:02:34,120 --> 00:02:35,388
HURTING HIM RIGHT AWAY

63
00:02:35,455 --> 00:02:38,758
-I only care if I get hurt. Okay?
-Okay. I'm scared now.

64
00:02:38,825 --> 00:02:40,393
-And you need that honesty.
-That's right.

65
00:02:40,460 --> 00:02:41,461
It's important.

66
00:02:41,528 --> 00:02:43,363
That way, these chefs will

67
00:02:43,429 --> 00:02:45,665
reflect on themselves and improve.

68
00:02:46,666 --> 00:02:47,667
You can improve.

69
00:02:47,734 --> 00:02:51,004
-Many of the chefs are your fans.
-Thank you.

70
00:02:51,070 --> 00:02:53,206
Especially, Chef Sung-jun.

71
00:02:53,273 --> 00:02:56,776
I heard you couldn't even sleep last night
when you heard Myung-soo was

72
00:02:56,843 --> 00:02:58,811
-coming to today's shoot.
-Really?

73
00:02:58,878 --> 00:03:00,013
Actually, I grew up

74
00:03:00,079 --> 00:03:01,548
watching <i>Infinite Challenge.</i>

75
00:03:01,614 --> 00:03:03,616
I'm a so-called <i>Infinite Challenge</i> kid.

76
00:03:03,683 --> 00:03:06,553
-He is my favorite TV personality.
-Thank you.

77
00:03:06,619 --> 00:03:08,521
I feel the most nervous today.

78
00:03:08,588 --> 00:03:12,225
Our show has featured
many different celebrities so far.

79
00:03:12,292 --> 00:03:14,827
-And Myung-soo is your favorite?
-He really is.

80
00:03:14,894 --> 00:03:16,296
He's a true fan.

81
00:03:16,362 --> 00:03:19,032
Many of my fans are smart.

82
00:03:19,699 --> 00:03:22,302
-That was sudden.
-He has a weak spot for compliments.

83
00:03:22,368 --> 00:03:24,904
They're mostly successful.
Many of them are a big success.

84
00:03:24,971 --> 00:03:27,574
-He's like that.
-Stop mixing in English.

85
00:03:27,640 --> 00:03:29,375
I do agree that

86
00:03:29,442 --> 00:03:31,711
-Chef Sung-jun is a smart man.
-Right?

87
00:03:31,778 --> 00:03:35,448
When he shows his respect for something,

88
00:03:35,515 --> 00:03:39,185
<i>it's because it'll help him</i>
<i>promote himself.</i>

89
00:03:39,252 --> 00:03:40,320
Are you taking advantage of them?

90
00:03:40,386 --> 00:03:44,424
We're a chess piece in his promotion.
He's such a smart man.

91
00:03:44,490 --> 00:03:46,693
Choi Hyun-suk or Park Myung-soo?

92
00:03:46,759 --> 00:03:49,295
In one, two, three.

93
00:03:49,362 --> 00:03:51,831
WILL HIS ROLE MODEL BE A CHEF?

94
00:03:51,898 --> 00:03:53,866
OR WILL IT BE
HIS FAVORITE TV PERSONALITY?

95
00:03:53,933 --> 00:03:55,568
In one, two, three.

96
00:03:55,635 --> 00:03:57,670
Park Myung-soo.

97
00:03:57,737 --> 00:03:59,806
HIS FOREVER FAVORITE
TV PERSONALITY

98
00:03:59,872 --> 00:04:01,241
That's amazing.

99
00:04:01,307 --> 00:04:02,875
-He'll make it big.
-He will?

100
00:04:02,942 --> 00:04:05,211
-He'll be Korea's best until the end.
-I see.

101
00:04:05,278 --> 00:04:07,280
There's another fan.

102
00:04:07,347 --> 00:04:10,650
Gyeong-jun, you're also a huge fan of his?

103
00:04:10,717 --> 00:04:13,586
I'm also an <i>Infinite Challenge</i> kid.
I love his quotes.

104
00:04:13,653 --> 00:04:15,722
His quotes? Myung-soo's quotes?

105
00:04:15,788 --> 00:04:17,257
Anything you remember?

106
00:04:17,323 --> 00:04:19,125
"The early bird is tired."

107
00:04:19,192 --> 00:04:20,660
"The early bird is tired."

108
00:04:20,727 --> 00:04:23,296
-<i>Early bird, very tired.</i>
-The early bird. Yes.

109
00:04:23,363 --> 00:04:25,064
<i>Early bird, very tired.</i>

110
00:04:25,131 --> 00:04:26,866
"Little and often ends up just little."

111
00:04:27,700 --> 00:04:29,669
"Kind words make people take you lightly."

112
00:04:29,736 --> 00:04:31,537
"Patience thrice makes you a pushover."

113
00:04:31,604 --> 00:04:33,640
"What are you looking at? Get lost."
Something like that.

114
00:04:34,040 --> 00:04:36,409
You memorized your own quotes.

115
00:04:36,476 --> 00:04:39,445
-You memorized them.
-No, I said them, so I remember.

116
00:04:39,512 --> 00:04:42,715
-I did that during <i>Infinite Challenge</i>.
-"Keep going even if you break."

117
00:04:42,782 --> 00:04:45,385
Back then, he…

118
00:04:45,451 --> 00:04:46,619
-I'm sorry.
-The old days?

119
00:04:46,686 --> 00:04:48,521
Hey, yellow head.

120
00:04:48,988 --> 00:04:50,823
CALLING OUT THE YELLOW HEAD
WHO TALKED WHILE HE TALKED

121
00:04:50,890 --> 00:04:52,892
-Yellow Head.
-I was talking about WIUGDC.

122
00:04:52,959 --> 00:04:55,395
-Why are you… WIUGDC?
-Yes.

123
00:04:55,461 --> 00:04:57,397
-He also mentioned my quote.
-What's WIUGDC?

124
00:04:57,463 --> 00:05:00,033
"What's Important is the Unwavering Grit
Despite the Challenges."

125
00:05:00,099 --> 00:05:03,136
Keep going despite the challenges.
We face one every day.

126
00:05:03,202 --> 00:05:06,773
Look at Matfia. He's writing it down.

127
00:05:06,839 --> 00:05:09,742
-People like that become successful.
-"Unwavering Grit Despite the Challenges."

128
00:05:09,809 --> 00:05:11,644
Look how he's writing it down.

129
00:05:11,711 --> 00:05:12,712
Wait, hey.

130
00:05:12,779 --> 00:05:14,647
-Is that for YouTube?
-"If you don't do it, someone else will."

131
00:05:14,714 --> 00:05:19,619
Why are you writing down his quote
in <i>Chef Hyun-suk's Greatest Quotes</i>?

132
00:05:22,021 --> 00:05:24,090
-He crossed out my name.
-Hyun-suk's name.

133
00:05:24,657 --> 00:05:26,225
BABY SHOW-OFF CHEF'S
SHOCKING BETRAYAL

134
00:05:26,292 --> 00:05:28,861
-He changes the name to Myung-soo.
-Matfia will make it big.

135
00:05:28,928 --> 00:05:29,996
It's a huge mess.

136
00:05:30,063 --> 00:05:32,365
-I told you this would happen.
-This is harsh.

137
00:05:32,432 --> 00:05:34,600
-That he'll only take advantage of you?
-And he did.

138
00:05:34,667 --> 00:05:36,169
Sung-jun's a smart guy.

139
00:05:36,235 --> 00:05:38,338
-He jumped ship right away.
-How clever.

140
00:05:38,404 --> 00:05:43,276
And now, let's go through
Myung-soo's fridge.

141
00:05:43,343 --> 00:05:45,011
-I'm looking forward to it.
-Yes.

142
00:05:45,078 --> 00:05:46,746
We're shooting on a Monday, right?

143
00:05:46,813 --> 00:05:51,217
So, Sunday at 2 p.m., a moving company
barged in and cleaned out everything.

144
00:05:51,284 --> 00:05:55,855
This morning, Min-seo, my daughter, said,
"Dad, where's that thing I was eating?"

145
00:05:55,922 --> 00:05:58,825
We were both busy,
so I never told her about this.

146
00:05:58,891 --> 00:06:02,328
She said, "Dad, what happened?
Where's all my food?"

147
00:06:02,395 --> 00:06:04,364
I told her I'd be on <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>,

148
00:06:04,430 --> 00:06:06,566
and she finally understood.

149
00:06:06,632 --> 00:06:09,001
-She said, "Oh, <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>?"
-What a relief.

150
00:06:09,068 --> 00:06:11,471
-They took everything.
-Everything including water.

151
00:06:11,537 --> 00:06:13,172
You even took my frozen dumplings.

152
00:06:13,239 --> 00:06:15,875
That's the foundation of this show.

153
00:06:15,942 --> 00:06:17,810
-We're very thorough.
-Yes.

154
00:06:17,877 --> 00:06:20,747
You have to make great dishes today.
If you don't…

155
00:06:20,813 --> 00:06:23,683
That's it, then. You'll have to leave.

156
00:06:23,750 --> 00:06:26,386
-Bet your license on this.
-Seriously?

157
00:06:26,452 --> 00:06:29,389
-That's so hard.
-We've never had a fridge owner like this.

158
00:06:29,455 --> 00:06:32,692
-You can expect a cutthroat review.
-Of course.

159
00:06:32,759 --> 00:06:34,460
It's the first time on TV.

160
00:06:34,527 --> 00:06:36,362
It's just another fridge.

161
00:06:36,429 --> 00:06:38,564
-Everyone's fridge is different.
-There's nothing first about it.

162
00:06:38,631 --> 00:06:40,433
We all live the same way.

163
00:06:40,500 --> 00:06:42,402
Don't we all have similar things
in the fridge?

164
00:06:42,468 --> 00:06:44,504
-So it's nothing special? Just ordinary?
-It isn't.

165
00:06:44,570 --> 00:06:46,372
-You think we all live the same way.
-Yes.

166
00:06:46,439 --> 00:06:49,175
We present Myung-soo's fridge!

167
00:06:49,242 --> 00:06:50,977
WHAT'S IN HIS FRIDGE?

168
00:06:51,043 --> 00:06:52,044
He's got a lot of stuff.

169
00:06:52,111 --> 00:06:53,479
We present Myung-soo's fridge!

170
00:06:53,546 --> 00:06:56,048
-Ta-da!
-He's got a lot of stuff.

171
00:06:56,115 --> 00:06:58,651
-It's very clean.
-It's neat.

172
00:06:58,718 --> 00:07:01,554
-The bottom shelf is full of alcohol.
-He has so many cans of beer.

173
00:07:01,621 --> 00:07:03,823
-My gosh. This thing.
-What is it?

174
00:07:03,890 --> 00:07:05,525
-My gosh. This thing.
-What is it?

175
00:07:05,591 --> 00:07:07,360
These are caviars.

176
00:07:07,427 --> 00:07:09,862
We don't all have caviar at home.

177
00:07:09,929 --> 00:07:13,800
-I wonder.
-I have no idea why we have caviar.

178
00:07:13,866 --> 00:07:16,436
-Stop lying. Really?
-Why do we have caviar?

179
00:07:16,502 --> 00:07:18,905
-Do you not eat it at home?
-My kid must've brought it,

180
00:07:18,971 --> 00:07:20,640
or it could've been a present.

181
00:07:20,706 --> 00:07:23,476
His kid gets caviar as a present?
From whom?

182
00:07:23,543 --> 00:07:27,747
But I have no recollection of eating it.
I haven't had caviar.

183
00:07:27,814 --> 00:07:30,950
-He has truffle sauce!
-Truffle sauces.

184
00:07:31,017 --> 00:07:33,186
-I got those as a present too.
-It's just like my fridge.

185
00:07:33,252 --> 00:07:36,456
I've never had that at home.
We got them as a present.

186
00:07:36,522 --> 00:07:37,757
Do you like truffles or not?

187
00:07:37,824 --> 00:07:40,793
-I do.
-You can use it up today.

188
00:07:40,860 --> 00:07:41,928
Yes, do it.

189
00:07:41,994 --> 00:07:43,429
-Can they use it?
-Everything, please.

190
00:07:43,496 --> 00:07:45,465
Is there anything you can't eat?

191
00:07:45,531 --> 00:07:47,867
No, not at all. Who hates caviar?

192
00:07:47,934 --> 00:07:51,671
He doesn't know why he has these,
but you're free to use them all.

193
00:07:51,737 --> 00:07:54,607
-Sung-ju, I have a question.
-What is it?

194
00:07:54,674 --> 00:07:56,576
What are those tiny things?

195
00:07:56,642 --> 00:07:58,945
-This one?
-They don't eat Korean food.

196
00:07:59,011 --> 00:08:00,513
-Capers?
-Capers.

197
00:08:00,580 --> 00:08:03,082
-Do you enjoy capers? Was it a present?
-Here's the thing.

198
00:08:03,149 --> 00:08:06,486
It's my family fridge,
so I didn't know what we had.

199
00:08:06,552 --> 00:08:08,988
It may not be mine, so I'm not so sure.

200
00:08:09,055 --> 00:08:11,491
Which shelf do you often go to?

201
00:08:11,557 --> 00:08:14,727
-The very bottom one. Beer. Reeb.
-Reeb?

202
00:08:14,794 --> 00:08:16,829
-I call it reeb.
-These?

203
00:08:16,896 --> 00:08:21,200
I usually have six 500 ml cans.
A total of 3,000 cc.

204
00:08:21,868 --> 00:08:23,202
-At home?
-Yes.

205
00:08:23,269 --> 00:08:25,338
-What do you usually eat with beer?
-Food?

206
00:08:25,404 --> 00:08:27,507
Is this what you eat?

207
00:08:27,573 --> 00:08:29,275
-Yes, right.
-Dried squid and filefish fillet.

208
00:08:29,342 --> 00:08:31,477
I love those things.
The funky dried fish flavor.

209
00:08:31,544 --> 00:08:33,212
I love dried filefish fillet, squid,

210
00:08:33,279 --> 00:08:35,781
-pollack, codfish, and such snacks.
-And cuttlefish too.

211
00:08:35,848 --> 00:08:38,150
When I go home and drink alone,

212
00:08:38,217 --> 00:08:40,453
I always get six cans ready.

213
00:08:40,520 --> 00:08:42,421
Then I pull out dried pollack

214
00:08:42,488 --> 00:08:45,424
and roast it. I don't want anyone's help.
I have to do it.

215
00:08:45,491 --> 00:08:47,693
-Do you make it crispy?
-Other people don't get it right.

216
00:08:47,760 --> 00:08:50,630
I get those ready,
put music on, and start drinking.

217
00:08:50,696 --> 00:08:52,398
Do you dip it in mayonnaise?

218
00:08:52,465 --> 00:08:54,534
-No. If I eat it with sauce,
-He doesn't.

219
00:08:54,600 --> 00:08:56,903
-I can't enjoy the dried fish taste.
-He likes that taste.

220
00:08:56,969 --> 00:08:58,971
-The fishiness.
-It has to smell like dried seafood.

221
00:08:59,038 --> 00:09:01,374
My hand also smells after a while,
so I end up biting my finger too.

222
00:09:01,440 --> 00:09:02,508
Stop lying.

223
00:09:02,575 --> 00:09:03,743
Of course, it's a lie.

224
00:09:05,044 --> 00:09:06,646
Of course, it is. How can I eat my finger?

225
00:09:06,712 --> 00:09:09,081
-Stop teasing your elder.
-Show some respect!

226
00:09:09,148 --> 00:09:10,983
It's not like we die in order.
You aren't much older.

227
00:09:11,050 --> 00:09:12,718
-We don't die in order.
-What elder?

228
00:09:12,785 --> 00:09:15,621
Wait, he must've received this in person.

229
00:09:15,688 --> 00:09:18,824
-Yes, that's Jisoo of BLACKPINK.
-Jisoo.

230
00:09:18,891 --> 00:09:21,460
When she came to my radio show,

231
00:09:21,527 --> 00:09:25,831
she got me the lemon <i>cheong</i>
because I had a sore throat.

232
00:09:25,898 --> 00:09:27,366
She got it as a present.

233
00:09:27,433 --> 00:09:29,035
So you're friends with BLACKPINK?

234
00:09:29,101 --> 00:09:30,937
<i>We're very close.</i>

235
00:09:31,003 --> 00:09:35,374
I also heard you were close to IU.

236
00:09:35,441 --> 00:09:38,711
She always sends me presents
whenever the holidays come around.

237
00:09:38,778 --> 00:09:43,149
IU said she had a list of people
she sends presents to.

238
00:09:43,215 --> 00:09:47,954
So she sends something to people
she's grateful to.

239
00:09:48,020 --> 00:09:49,555
It's been a decade with her.

240
00:09:49,622 --> 00:09:51,390
-I see.
-And every holiday,

241
00:09:51,457 --> 00:09:53,593
she doesn't send the same thing,
but something different every year.

242
00:09:53,659 --> 00:09:55,528
What has she given you?

243
00:09:55,595 --> 00:09:56,862
Beef, something everyone likes.

244
00:09:56,929 --> 00:10:00,066
She takes turns and sends things like
beef, ginseng, honey, and more.

245
00:10:00,132 --> 00:10:02,602
-She changes it around.
-And truffle too.

246
00:10:02,668 --> 00:10:05,771
Let's keep going down. You got some fruit.
Do you like strawberries?

247
00:10:05,838 --> 00:10:08,341
-I love strawberries.
-You do?

248
00:10:08,407 --> 00:10:10,209
-Kiwi and cherry tomatoes.
-What about kiwi and cherry tomatoes?

249
00:10:10,276 --> 00:10:13,179
I love them. I love all kinds of fruit.

250
00:10:13,245 --> 00:10:16,349
-He loves fruit.
-I always have some in the morning.

251
00:10:16,415 --> 00:10:19,785
And vegetables. Cabbage, napa cabbage.

252
00:10:19,852 --> 00:10:21,454
-I love veggies.
-You do?

253
00:10:21,520 --> 00:10:24,056
-I see.
-I like to steam the cabbage

254
00:10:24,123 --> 00:10:25,958
-and eat it with <i>doenjang</i>.
-Like <i>ssamjang</i>.

255
00:10:26,025 --> 00:10:28,327
I love it. I enjoy it a lot.

256
00:10:28,394 --> 00:10:30,596
-Do you like to steam it?
-It's good for you.

257
00:10:30,663 --> 00:10:31,731
It's my favorite.

258
00:10:31,797 --> 00:10:34,000
Let's check out the freezer.

259
00:10:34,066 --> 00:10:36,135
I feel bad that I don't have much to show.

260
00:10:36,202 --> 00:10:38,671
I found half-dried pollack.
No, frozen pollack.

261
00:10:38,738 --> 00:10:41,874
-That's really good.
-I like that sharp tang.

262
00:10:41,941 --> 00:10:43,075
-Like dried seafood?
-Yes.

263
00:10:43,142 --> 00:10:47,279
Yes, something you dry or half-dry.
I love half-dried or frozen pollacks.

264
00:10:47,346 --> 00:10:49,949
-I found abalones too.
-Those are expensive.

265
00:10:50,016 --> 00:10:51,851
-I found a shelf full of seafood.
-Right.

266
00:10:51,917 --> 00:10:53,319
I like seafood.

267
00:10:53,386 --> 00:10:55,221
You must like fish.

268
00:10:55,287 --> 00:10:56,522
-He likes seafood.
-I only eat a few kinds.

269
00:10:56,589 --> 00:10:58,924
Mackerel and pollack.

270
00:10:58,991 --> 00:11:00,426
Other fish gross me out,
so I can't eat them.

271
00:11:00,493 --> 00:11:02,361
-Do you enjoy fishy seafood?
-What?

272
00:11:02,428 --> 00:11:04,930
-Do you like it? I don't.
-Mackerels are fishy, though.

273
00:11:04,997 --> 00:11:07,433
I found meat. Do you enjoy meat?

274
00:11:07,500 --> 00:11:10,469
I do. I especially enjoy it
when it's someone else's treat.

275
00:11:10,536 --> 00:11:12,538
I think we bought that pack.

276
00:11:12,605 --> 00:11:14,740
I don't like it
when it's braised or soupy.

277
00:11:14,807 --> 00:11:16,609
HE DOESN'T LIKE MEAT
COOKED IN WATER

278
00:11:16,676 --> 00:11:19,612
-I oddly don't like it when it's in soup.
-Those kinds.

279
00:11:19,679 --> 00:11:20,880
What about boiled pork?

280
00:11:20,946 --> 00:11:23,215
I rarely eat it. I oddly don't like it.

281
00:11:23,282 --> 00:11:26,118
-What about beef tartare?
-I do eat that.

282
00:11:26,185 --> 00:11:28,087
It's fine
as long as it's not cooked in water.

283
00:11:28,154 --> 00:11:30,623
And down here. Do you like rice cake?

284
00:11:30,690 --> 00:11:32,892
-I do like rice cakes.
-It looks like <i>injeolmi</i>.

285
00:11:32,958 --> 00:11:34,660
-I like rice cakes.
-Those look good.

286
00:11:34,727 --> 00:11:36,495
<i>Injeolmi</i>.
So you like both bread and <i>injeolmi</i>?

287
00:11:36,562 --> 00:11:38,164
I love rice cakes.

288
00:11:38,230 --> 00:11:39,632
Rice cake or bread?

289
00:11:39,699 --> 00:11:42,601
I love financiers.

290
00:11:42,668 --> 00:11:43,836
That's bread.

291
00:11:43,903 --> 00:11:48,441
I look like a French nobleman,
so I enjoy confectionery like financiers.

292
00:11:48,507 --> 00:11:50,643
-Western cake.
-Western cake and <i>songpyeon</i>.

293
00:11:50,710 --> 00:11:52,912
Room temperature ingredients.
I see some shredded dried pollack.

294
00:11:52,978 --> 00:11:54,380
Do you use it to make hangover soup?

295
00:11:54,447 --> 00:11:57,049
It's my breakfast.
I love dried pollack soup.

296
00:11:57,116 --> 00:11:59,018
Everyone loves <i>bugeoguk</i>,
dried pollack soup with bean sprouts.

297
00:11:59,085 --> 00:12:02,521
I like that dried fish flavor
like shredded dried pollack.

298
00:12:02,588 --> 00:12:04,356
I love all kinds of dried seafood.

299
00:12:04,423 --> 00:12:06,392
Things like dried codfish and pollack.

300
00:12:06,459 --> 00:12:08,928
That was all for Myung-soo's fridge.

301
00:12:08,994 --> 00:12:14,633
It's time to figure out Myung-soo's order
and the contenders.

302
00:12:14,700 --> 00:12:17,169
What kind of dishes does he want to eat?

303
00:12:17,236 --> 00:12:19,538
Let's find out the orders.

304
00:12:19,605 --> 00:12:22,742
Myung-soo's first order.

305
00:12:22,808 --> 00:12:26,078
-Grandpa Myung-soo wants pics.
-Yes.

306
00:12:26,145 --> 00:12:28,714
Grandpa Myung-soo wants pics. Yes.

307
00:12:28,781 --> 00:12:31,584
-Grandpa Park Myung-soo's my channel.
-I see.

308
00:12:31,650 --> 00:12:33,953
Click, subscribe,
have the notifications on.

309
00:12:34,019 --> 00:12:35,721
-Subscribe and like.
-Please do that.

310
00:12:35,788 --> 00:12:37,490
-Hence, "Grandpa Myung-soo."
-Yes.

311
00:12:37,556 --> 00:12:42,027
I rarely take photos when I eat out.
I don't like doing that.

312
00:12:42,094 --> 00:12:44,463
But when I see something
that's unique and appealing,

313
00:12:44,530 --> 00:12:47,566
I take some pictures for my kid.
She likes to see those.

314
00:12:47,633 --> 00:12:49,401
-It must look pretty.
-The plating is important.

315
00:12:49,468 --> 00:12:53,105
Please make something
that'll touch my heart

316
00:12:53,172 --> 00:12:56,642
-and will make me want to take pictures.
-Something with a great presentation.

317
00:12:56,709 --> 00:12:58,310
Please do that.

318
00:12:58,377 --> 00:13:00,412
What if it's pretty
but doesn't taste good?

319
00:13:00,479 --> 00:13:03,082
-Then they'll be criticized.
-Criticisms.

320
00:13:03,149 --> 00:13:04,250
-That's a given.
-It can't just look good.

321
00:13:04,316 --> 00:13:06,018
-Of course.
-Taste should come first.

322
00:13:06,085 --> 00:13:07,887
Show us the second order.

323
00:13:07,953 --> 00:13:09,421
Myung-soo's order.

324
00:13:09,488 --> 00:13:11,524
Grandpa Myung-soo, alone with beer.

325
00:13:11,590 --> 00:13:13,259
Drinking beer alone?

326
00:13:13,325 --> 00:13:16,028
-I like beer, so a dish to eat with that.
-Something with dried fish.

327
00:13:16,095 --> 00:13:17,630
I want to be moved,

328
00:13:17,696 --> 00:13:20,933
and I want it to help
make beer taste even better.

329
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:22,501
Do you like heavier dishes? Or lighter?

330
00:13:22,568 --> 00:13:25,037
Lighter. I don't like heavy dishes.

331
00:13:25,104 --> 00:13:28,207
I only watch lightweight boxing matches.
Never heavyweight.

332
00:13:28,274 --> 00:13:30,643
-You want more beer, so something light.
-Yes.

333
00:13:30,709 --> 00:13:34,647
You're watching the revenge special
with people full of spite.

334
00:13:34,713 --> 00:13:39,585
Chef Fabri singled out
Chef Sung-jun for his return match.

335
00:13:39,652 --> 00:13:42,655
Chef Nam-no,
I heard you had a request too.

336
00:13:42,721 --> 00:13:45,591
-Yes, today, I came to get him.
-Me?

337
00:13:45,658 --> 00:13:46,725
-You mean me?
-Yes.

338
00:13:46,792 --> 00:13:48,561
I lost against him once before.

339
00:13:49,261 --> 00:13:50,629
That takes a huge toll on you.

340
00:13:50,696 --> 00:13:53,866
-People always win and lose on the show.
-Yes.

341
00:13:53,933 --> 00:13:56,335
My staff look at me differently.

342
00:13:56,402 --> 00:13:57,870
It's not a big deal, but it bothers you.

343
00:13:57,937 --> 00:14:01,106
Nam-no, you've been on the show,
so can you let Fabri choose first?

344
00:14:01,173 --> 00:14:02,942
-Yes.
-I'm a new guy here.

345
00:14:03,008 --> 00:14:04,243
Please.

346
00:14:04,910 --> 00:14:07,913
Sung-jun must follow
whatever Fabri chooses.

347
00:14:07,980 --> 00:14:11,717
I'm very confident
about making pretty dishes.

348
00:14:11,784 --> 00:14:13,552
-So the picture.
-Yes.

349
00:14:13,619 --> 00:14:19,592
-Fabri is famous for his presentation.
-He is.

350
00:14:19,658 --> 00:14:21,627
He takes "Grandpa Myung-soo wants pics."

351
00:14:21,694 --> 00:14:26,365
Then Nam-no and Poong automatically gets
"Grandpa Myung-soo, alone with beer."

352
00:14:26,432 --> 00:14:31,070
Let us begin the 15-minute cook-off
for Myung-soo!

353
00:14:33,806 --> 00:14:38,444
<i>This is the first round</i>
<i>with ingredients from Myung-soo's fridge.</i>

354
00:14:38,510 --> 00:14:42,081
This is their third return match.

355
00:14:42,147 --> 00:14:45,050
<i>A chef who kept his Michelin star</i>
<i>for 15 years in Italy,</i>

356
00:14:45,117 --> 00:14:49,622
a real Italian chef, Fabri is up.

357
00:14:49,688 --> 00:14:52,324
This chef turned a tough corner
when he fought against Fabri,

358
00:14:52,391 --> 00:14:54,393
-then went on to win the show.
-That's right.

359
00:14:54,460 --> 00:14:56,962
A wannabe Italian, Napoli Matfia.

360
00:14:57,029 --> 00:14:59,531
-He's a fake.
-This round is between the two.

361
00:14:59,598 --> 00:15:02,268
-Chef Fabri is absolutely determined.
-Yes.

362
00:15:02,334 --> 00:15:05,537
In Korea,
people don't wear that headband often

363
00:15:05,604 --> 00:15:07,373
-unless they're absolutely determined.
-No, right.

364
00:15:07,439 --> 00:15:08,507
And it's a red one too.

365
00:15:08,574 --> 00:15:10,009
He's either determined or ill.

366
00:15:10,075 --> 00:15:12,478
-Determined, ill, or doing aerobics.
-Aerobics.

367
00:15:12,544 --> 00:15:14,647
One, two, three. Like that.

368
00:15:14,713 --> 00:15:15,848
It's my passion.

369
00:15:15,915 --> 00:15:19,151
<i>-Passion.</i>
<i>-It's red for passion.</i>

370
00:15:19,218 --> 00:15:20,920
Passion!

371
00:15:20,986 --> 00:15:23,322
I'm here to show you

372
00:15:23,389 --> 00:15:27,126
the good old original Italian revenge.

373
00:15:28,527 --> 00:15:30,262
The Italian revenge.

374
00:15:30,329 --> 00:15:32,131
Fabri, from what I heard,

375
00:15:32,197 --> 00:15:35,567
you and your family immigrated to Korea.

376
00:15:35,634 --> 00:15:36,936
-That's right.
-Am I right?

377
00:15:37,002 --> 00:15:38,070
Did you immigrate?

378
00:15:38,137 --> 00:15:39,138
NODDING

379
00:15:39,204 --> 00:15:41,073
-I see.
-He moved here for good.

380
00:15:41,140 --> 00:15:43,208
-Kor-Talian.
-Kor-Talian.

381
00:15:43,275 --> 00:15:45,711
Honestly speaking,
I really don't like his outfit today.

382
00:15:45,778 --> 00:15:47,646
-Why not?
-What's wrong?

383
00:15:47,713 --> 00:15:51,417
-The Italian flag has green, white, red.
-You're right!

384
00:15:51,483 --> 00:15:54,620
-Yes, that's France!
-That's the French flag.

385
00:15:55,854 --> 00:15:56,855
SWOOSH

386
00:15:57,423 --> 00:15:58,958
ABANDONED

387
00:15:59,024 --> 00:16:00,759
He's wearing the French flag!

388
00:16:00,826 --> 00:16:01,994
He's not here to represent Italy.

389
00:16:02,061 --> 00:16:03,729
He took it off.

390
00:16:03,796 --> 00:16:06,699
I realized it just now. Thank you.

391
00:16:06,765 --> 00:16:09,101
Fabri just changed his apron.

392
00:16:09,168 --> 00:16:12,771
-France? That's preposterous. No way.
-You noticed it.

393
00:16:12,838 --> 00:16:14,773
-He's now the German flag.
-He's the German flag.

394
00:16:15,941 --> 00:16:18,210
-The German flag.
-It's the German flag now.

395
00:16:18,277 --> 00:16:20,379
-His aprons aren't working out.
-Wait.

396
00:16:20,446 --> 00:16:22,214
He's the Indonesian flag.

397
00:16:22,281 --> 00:16:23,482
-He's the German flag.
-The Indonesian flag.

398
00:16:23,549 --> 00:16:24,750
Stop it.

399
00:16:24,817 --> 00:16:27,553
-Stop it now.
-Stop it.

400
00:16:27,619 --> 00:16:29,188
He doesn't have another apron.

401
00:16:29,254 --> 00:16:32,658
-He'd be just a chef without the headband.
-Right.

402
00:16:33,592 --> 00:16:35,327
CHEF FABRI'S INGREDIENTS: CHERRY TOMATOES,
TTEOKBOKKI RICE CAKES, SOUP STOCK, RADISH

403
00:16:35,394 --> 00:16:37,096
MACKEREL, SHREDDED DRIED POLLACK, ARUGULA,
SOFT TOFU, CAPER, HALLABONG

404
00:16:37,162 --> 00:16:40,199
First, Chef Fabri. What's your dish?

405
00:16:40,265 --> 00:16:43,702
Rearrange Mackerel.

406
00:16:43,769 --> 00:16:44,937
-What?
-What?

407
00:16:45,004 --> 00:16:47,139
-Revenge Mackerel.
-Revenge Mackerel?

408
00:16:47,206 --> 00:16:49,141
-Oh, Revenge Mackerel.
-Revenge Mackerel.

409
00:16:49,208 --> 00:16:51,677
-Mackerel.
-A mackerel dish.

410
00:16:51,744 --> 00:16:52,745
-He'll use mackerel.
-Mackerel.

411
00:16:52,811 --> 00:16:54,079
Bang. Yes.

412
00:16:54,146 --> 00:16:57,349
I'll make mackerel confit.

413
00:16:57,416 --> 00:16:59,618
-What?
-I'll confit the fish.

414
00:16:59,685 --> 00:17:01,520
-Do you know what confit is?
-What?

415
00:17:01,587 --> 00:17:02,621
Confetti?

416
00:17:03,922 --> 00:17:04,923
What's confit?

417
00:17:04,990 --> 00:17:07,292
Can he confit it thoroughly
over just 15 minutes?

418
00:17:07,359 --> 00:17:09,228
-It seems impossible.
-Does he know the rules?

419
00:17:09,294 --> 00:17:11,130
It'll be a tough challenge.

420
00:17:11,196 --> 00:17:16,368
I'll cook it slowly in oil
around 90 degrees in temperature.

421
00:17:16,435 --> 00:17:19,872
Then I'll make just the top seem like
it's been broiled.

422
00:17:19,938 --> 00:17:22,307
In Tuscan cuisine,

423
00:17:22,374 --> 00:17:25,210
there's a salad called <i>panzanella</i>.

424
00:17:25,277 --> 00:17:29,048
It's supposed to be made with bread,

425
00:17:29,114 --> 00:17:30,416
but he didn't have any.

426
00:17:30,482 --> 00:17:33,685
-Will he bake bread?
-He enjoys rice cakes, so I'll use those.

427
00:17:33,752 --> 00:17:36,055
-Are you using rice cake?
-Rice cake <i>panzanella</i>.

428
00:17:36,121 --> 00:17:37,756
Rice cake and mackerel?

429
00:17:37,823 --> 00:17:40,726
Will rice cake and mackerel
work well together?

430
00:17:40,793 --> 00:17:43,896
I love seafood,
especially mackerel and pollack.

431
00:17:43,962 --> 00:17:45,531
He doesn't know what confit is,

432
00:17:45,597 --> 00:17:47,166
-but he does know his mackerel.
-I don't know that.

433
00:17:48,100 --> 00:17:49,868
CHEF SUNG-JUN'S INGREDIENTS: SHRIMP MEAT,
SHREDDED DRIED POLLACK, NAPA CABBAGE

434
00:17:49,935 --> 00:17:51,703
CABBAGE, SALTED SHRIMP, RADISH,
FROZEN POLLACK, SCALLOP, TOFU, TUNA SAUCE

435
00:17:51,770 --> 00:17:54,406
Up against him is Chef Sung-jun.
What's your dish?

436
00:17:54,473 --> 00:17:55,808
The dish I prepared is this.

437
00:17:57,009 --> 00:18:00,412
<i>I Came to Make Flower Pasta</i>

438
00:18:02,681 --> 00:18:04,349
Was that Jisoo's song?

439
00:18:04,416 --> 00:18:06,618
Jisoo and I are the same age.

440
00:18:06,685 --> 00:18:08,287
Oh, flower pasta.

441
00:18:08,353 --> 00:18:10,589
His voice trembled a little.

442
00:18:10,656 --> 00:18:12,424
He has taken after Ho-young.

443
00:18:12,491 --> 00:18:15,127
HE'S DIVERSIFYING HIS PORTFOLIO

444
00:18:15,794 --> 00:18:16,795
What's flower pasta?

445
00:18:16,862 --> 00:18:20,532
The dish I prepared today is
called tagliatelle <i>ripiene</i>.

446
00:18:20,599 --> 00:18:24,236
There's a dumpling-style pasta
shaped like a flower.

447
00:18:24,303 --> 00:18:26,238
A budding flower. It's now spring,

448
00:18:26,305 --> 00:18:28,941
-so I'll make flower-shaped pasta.
-Spring is here.

449
00:18:29,007 --> 00:18:31,743
I'll make fresh pasta dough
and cook from scratch,

450
00:18:31,810 --> 00:18:34,580
-both the skin to the fillings.
-You'll make it now?

451
00:18:34,646 --> 00:18:36,415
-Fresh pasta?
-I'll make everything.

452
00:18:36,482 --> 00:18:40,219
And Myung-soo also said he liked
the flavor of bugeoguk.

453
00:18:40,285 --> 00:18:43,689
<i>I'll make the pollack sauce</i>
<i>inspired by that soup.</i>

454
00:18:43,755 --> 00:18:45,924
So it sounds like <i>bugeoguk </i>with dumplings.

455
00:18:45,991 --> 00:18:48,961
-It's the Italian version of it.
-The Italian version.

456
00:18:49,027 --> 00:18:50,496
-I see.
-I really like that.

457
00:18:50,562 --> 00:18:53,432
-Oh, my. You made a perfect choice.
-He loves that.

458
00:18:53,499 --> 00:18:57,769
And now, let us begin their cook-off.

459
00:18:58,904 --> 00:19:02,841
In real life, this is more than…

460
00:19:02,908 --> 00:19:03,976
It brings back old memories.

461
00:19:04,042 --> 00:19:06,979
Here we go. Please get ready.

462
00:19:07,045 --> 00:19:11,483
He's here to teach a lesson
to the fake Neapolitan.

463
00:19:11,550 --> 00:19:13,785
The real Italian, Chef Fabri.

464
00:19:13,852 --> 00:19:15,354
He believes both on <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>

465
00:19:15,420 --> 00:19:19,224
and <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>,
the winner will be Napoli Matfia.

466
00:19:19,291 --> 00:19:21,860
Chef Kwon Sung-jun is ready to fight him.

467
00:19:21,927 --> 00:19:26,131
Will Chef Fabri get his revenge?

468
00:19:26,198 --> 00:19:29,701
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

469
00:19:30,903 --> 00:19:34,506
TWO ITALIAN CHEFS
FACE EACH OTHER

470
00:19:34,573 --> 00:19:37,109
Fabri should probably rush things.

471
00:19:37,176 --> 00:19:39,211
-Yes, right.
-Yes.

472
00:19:39,278 --> 00:19:40,646
-Jeez.
-It's not lighting up.

473
00:19:40,712 --> 00:19:43,015
-Exactly. It's not easy to…
-Right there.

474
00:19:43,081 --> 00:19:44,216
-The heat.
-The red part.

475
00:19:44,283 --> 00:19:46,418
-Okay.
-He got it.

476
00:19:46,485 --> 00:19:47,753
1. OIL PAN
AND STIR-FRY DRIED POLLACK

477
00:19:47,819 --> 00:19:49,388
Are you stir-frying those right away?

478
00:19:49,454 --> 00:19:50,822
Is that dried pollack?

479
00:19:50,889 --> 00:19:52,324
Are you stir-frying those?

480
00:19:52,391 --> 00:19:53,792
Do people use pollacks in Italy?

481
00:19:53,859 --> 00:19:54,960
Pollacks? No.

482
00:19:55,027 --> 00:19:56,728
I've never seen it in Italy.

483
00:19:56,795 --> 00:19:58,163
I didn't think so.

484
00:19:58,230 --> 00:19:59,598
He's using dried pollack and mackerel.

485
00:19:59,665 --> 00:20:01,033
Hyun-suk.

486
00:20:01,099 --> 00:20:03,969
SHOOTING OUT SALT

487
00:20:04,036 --> 00:20:05,103
<i>He's a timid Hyun-suk.</i>

488
00:20:05,170 --> 00:20:07,806
<i>-He has his own style.</i>
<i>-Yes.</i>

489
00:20:07,873 --> 00:20:09,775
SWAG

490
00:20:09,841 --> 00:20:12,144
2. SEASON MACKEREL WITH SALT

491
00:20:13,245 --> 00:20:16,381
Sung-jun is preparing radish.

492
00:20:17,883 --> 00:20:21,186
HE BEGINS BY CHOPPING SKILLFULLY

493
00:20:21,753 --> 00:20:23,655
1. STIR-FRY SLICED RADISH,
SESAME OIL, AND MINCED GARLIC

494
00:20:23,722 --> 00:20:26,558
-Did he add sesame oil? He did.
-He did.

495
00:20:26,625 --> 00:20:28,827
HE GRABS SHREDDED DRIED POLLACK

496
00:20:30,162 --> 00:20:32,297
He's frying radish and garlic.

497
00:20:34,433 --> 00:20:36,935
CHOPPING AGAIN

498
00:20:37,002 --> 00:20:39,238
-Look at his chopping skills.
-Look at that.

499
00:20:39,304 --> 00:20:41,273
He's good with the knife, isn't he?

500
00:20:41,340 --> 00:20:43,375
-He's the winner of <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.
-<i>Bugeoguk </i>will taste great

501
00:20:43,442 --> 00:20:46,311
-if he just added water and boiled it.
-Yes, right?

502
00:20:47,246 --> 00:20:49,681
Look at the way he chops.

503
00:20:49,748 --> 00:20:51,917
He's going very fast.

504
00:20:52,684 --> 00:20:55,621
-I can't even see his hand.
-The cabbage!

505
00:20:55,687 --> 00:20:59,224
Sung-jun, you're amazing.

506
00:20:59,291 --> 00:21:01,226
Sung-jun, you're on fire.

507
00:21:01,960 --> 00:21:03,462
FEELING PROUD

508
00:21:03,528 --> 00:21:05,197
Sung-jun is on fire.

509
00:21:05,264 --> 00:21:06,732
Look how fast he is.

510
00:21:06,798 --> 00:21:09,201
Sung-jun moves very fast.

511
00:21:10,035 --> 00:21:12,404
That's why he's the winner.
He surprised me.

512
00:21:12,971 --> 00:21:14,406
SCRAMBLING

513
00:21:15,407 --> 00:21:16,808
Whoa. And…

514
00:21:17,876 --> 00:21:20,012
I'm already feeling hectic.

515
00:21:20,078 --> 00:21:22,481
All Fabri is doing is
burning the dried pollack.

516
00:21:22,547 --> 00:21:24,716
Fabri grabs a piece of radish too.

517
00:21:24,783 --> 00:21:27,152
HOW WELL DOES FABRI CHOP
AS AN ITALIAN MICHELIN-STAR CHEF?

518
00:21:27,886 --> 00:21:31,056
CHOP

519
00:21:31,123 --> 00:21:35,694
I think Fabri is almost as fast as I am.

520
00:21:36,495 --> 00:21:38,597
HE TOSSES THE SHREDDED
DRIED POLLACK AGAIN

521
00:21:39,531 --> 00:21:42,000
Fabri, are you roasting young pollack
like this is a bar?

522
00:21:42,067 --> 00:21:44,102
-That's all you're doing!
-Yes?

523
00:21:44,169 --> 00:21:45,537
Give me a moment.

524
00:21:46,505 --> 00:21:48,106
I thought this was a bar
that only served pollack.

525
00:21:48,173 --> 00:21:50,509
He must have a plan.
He stir-fries the pollack.

526
00:21:50,575 --> 00:21:51,943
It'll be fine as long as it's good.

527
00:21:52,878 --> 00:21:54,479
HE GRABS
SOME ROASTED DRIED POLLACK

528
00:21:54,546 --> 00:21:55,681
PUTTING THEM STRAIGHT IN THE OVEN

529
00:21:55,747 --> 00:21:57,683
-Are you putting those in the oven?
-The oven?

530
00:21:57,749 --> 00:21:59,051
He put some in the oven.

531
00:22:01,053 --> 00:22:03,488
3. ADD CHOPPED RADISH TO ROASTED
POLLACK AND CONTINUE TO STIR-FRY

532
00:22:03,555 --> 00:22:06,525
They're both using radish
and dried pollack.

533
00:22:06,591 --> 00:22:07,592
The same ingredients.

534
00:22:07,659 --> 00:22:10,896
I don't think Fabri used any oil.

535
00:22:10,962 --> 00:22:12,497
He just tossed some in.

536
00:22:12,564 --> 00:22:14,166
What? What now?

537
00:22:14,866 --> 00:22:20,005
4. ADD WATER, SOUP STOCK, AND SALT
TO THE STIR-FRY AND BOIL

538
00:22:20,072 --> 00:22:22,741
-He added salted shrimp.
-That must be the seasoning.

539
00:22:24,109 --> 00:22:26,311
It looks like he's making soup, <i>bugeoguk</i>.

540
00:22:27,579 --> 00:22:28,613
DROPS FROZEN POLLACK

541
00:22:28,680 --> 00:22:30,816
-And yes, the frozen pollack.
-Frozen pollack!

542
00:22:30,882 --> 00:22:33,051
-And yes, the frozen pollack.
-Frozen pollack!

543
00:22:33,118 --> 00:22:34,986
What is he doing?

544
00:22:35,053 --> 00:22:37,122
-Frozen pollack.
-He's adding more fermented flavor.

545
00:22:37,189 --> 00:22:38,457
Frozen pollack.

546
00:22:38,523 --> 00:22:40,359
He just added frozen pollack.

547
00:22:40,425 --> 00:22:42,494
That already looks delicious.

548
00:22:42,561 --> 00:22:45,797
It's a hangover soup.
Yang-rak would love that.

549
00:22:45,864 --> 00:22:47,232
He would.

550
00:22:47,299 --> 00:22:49,801
I'm sorry, but this is for me.
You can't cook for Yang-rak.

551
00:22:49,868 --> 00:22:52,404
What's he doing?

552
00:22:52,971 --> 00:22:56,141
HE PREPARES HALLABONG

553
00:22:56,842 --> 00:22:59,378
HE CUTS EVERY PIECE

554
00:23:00,145 --> 00:23:02,681
HE MAY BE SLOWER,
BUT HE CUTS WITH DELICATE TOUCHES

555
00:23:03,915 --> 00:23:06,485
-He's chopping capers.
-Capers.

556
00:23:06,551 --> 00:23:07,919
Capers.

557
00:23:09,488 --> 00:23:11,123
HALLABONG AND CAPERS

558
00:23:12,557 --> 00:23:13,892
CHOPS CHERRY TOMATOES
ONE BY ONE TOO

559
00:23:13,959 --> 00:23:16,128
Fabri is definitely slower.

560
00:23:18,096 --> 00:23:19,197
6. ADD SCALLOPS,
SHRIMP MEAT, STARCH,

561
00:23:19,264 --> 00:23:20,499
TUNA SAUCE, AND SESAME OIL
INTO A BLENDER

562
00:23:20,565 --> 00:23:21,967
-He's using lots of seafood.
-He is.

563
00:23:22,033 --> 00:23:25,704
-Scallops.
-Scallops and starch.

564
00:23:25,771 --> 00:23:28,106
Isn't that too much starch?

565
00:23:28,173 --> 00:23:30,075
Isn't that enough to make fish cake?

566
00:23:30,142 --> 00:23:32,444
Sung-jun, what are you blending?

567
00:23:32,511 --> 00:23:34,112
The dumpling filling.

568
00:23:35,213 --> 00:23:37,516
Chef Sung-jun added tofu.

569
00:23:37,582 --> 00:23:41,586
If you add tofu in the filling,
it'll taste more like Korean dumplings.

570
00:23:41,653 --> 00:23:42,654
HOW WILL THE FILLING TURN OUT?

571
00:23:43,221 --> 00:23:44,756
CHOPPING GREEN ONION

572
00:23:45,323 --> 00:23:47,025
ALREADY MESMERIZED BY HIS SKILLS

573
00:23:47,092 --> 00:23:48,693
My gosh, really.

574
00:23:52,464 --> 00:23:54,866
Sung-jun.

575
00:23:54,933 --> 00:23:57,202
-Are you doing okay?
-Fabri.

576
00:23:57,269 --> 00:23:59,004
Fabri just called Sung-jun.

577
00:23:59,070 --> 00:24:02,107
It'll turn out like
a Korean-Italian fusion dish.

578
00:24:03,708 --> 00:24:06,344
-Look at Fabri. What's he doing?
-Fabri just called Sung-jun.

579
00:24:06,411 --> 00:24:07,512
What are you up to?

580
00:24:07,579 --> 00:24:10,215
-He's extracting seeds from the tomatoes.
-He's doing it one by one.

581
00:24:10,282 --> 00:24:12,284
He doesn't have enough time to do that.

582
00:24:12,350 --> 00:24:14,085
He's removing the seeds.

583
00:24:14,152 --> 00:24:15,987
He's paying too much attention
on the small things.

584
00:24:16,054 --> 00:24:18,089
There must be a reason
why he can't use the seeds.

585
00:24:18,156 --> 00:24:20,492
It's an Italian dish, so trust him.
He's an Italian.

586
00:24:20,559 --> 00:24:22,527
Don't be so hard on an Italian
making an Italian dish.

587
00:24:22,594 --> 00:24:25,997
-He hasn't even begun with the confit.
-When will you do that?

588
00:24:26,064 --> 00:24:28,567
He's waiting for the mackerel
to be seasoned.

589
00:24:28,633 --> 00:24:31,036
Yes, you're right, Nam-no.

590
00:24:31,603 --> 00:24:32,838
Sung-jun.

591
00:24:32,904 --> 00:24:35,040
-Sung-jun.
-Fabri spends too long on the tomatoes.

592
00:24:35,106 --> 00:24:36,741
SUNG-JUN IS BUSY WORKING

593
00:24:36,808 --> 00:24:39,277
-What's that?
-That's gochujang.

594
00:24:39,344 --> 00:24:41,513
-Gochujang?
-He just dissolved it in water.

595
00:24:42,714 --> 00:24:44,950
He's using gochujang.

596
00:24:45,550 --> 00:24:47,486
GOCHUJANG WATER, READY TO GO

597
00:24:47,552 --> 00:24:50,121
He asked you to make a dish
that's photogenic,

598
00:24:50,188 --> 00:24:52,557
so the color would be important too.

599
00:24:52,624 --> 00:24:55,227
-Why did he use gochujang?
-That must be the dumpling skin.

600
00:24:55,293 --> 00:24:57,462
-Like <i>jangtteok</i>, gochujang pancake?
-Like <i>jangtteok</i>?

601
00:24:57,529 --> 00:24:58,530
He's pouring flour into that?

602
00:24:58,597 --> 00:25:00,866
He's making the dumpling skin.

603
00:25:00,932 --> 00:25:02,434
The dough is looking reddish.

604
00:25:02,501 --> 00:25:04,436
That's a lot.

605
00:25:05,604 --> 00:25:08,440
HE FINALLY FINISHED
PICKING OUT THE TOMATO SEEDS

606
00:25:08,507 --> 00:25:11,376
Fabri hasn't even begun with the mackerel.

607
00:25:11,443 --> 00:25:12,878
-Right?
-He has eight minutes.

608
00:25:13,512 --> 00:25:15,347
Whoa. Green onion.

609
00:25:15,413 --> 00:25:16,548
He's suddenly running.

610
00:25:16,615 --> 00:25:19,417
When will you begin the confit?

611
00:25:19,484 --> 00:25:20,752
When will you cook the mackerel?

612
00:25:20,819 --> 00:25:22,521
This looks like trouble.

613
00:25:22,587 --> 00:25:25,323
-Myung-soo, by any chance,
-Yes?

614
00:25:25,390 --> 00:25:26,558
you said you liked fermented flavor.

615
00:25:26,625 --> 00:25:27,659
Uncooked mackerel?

616
00:25:28,760 --> 00:25:31,129
-Isn't overly fermented?
-Uncooked mackerel can be good.

617
00:25:31,196 --> 00:25:32,564
You're harsh with your words.

618
00:25:32,631 --> 00:25:34,966
HE CHECKS THE OIL TEMPERATURE
TO CONFIT THE FISH

619
00:25:37,602 --> 00:25:39,838
SHOOTING OUT THE LASER

620
00:25:39,905 --> 00:25:41,339
A LASER ATTACK ON THE DOUGH

621
00:25:41,406 --> 00:25:43,241
-As we speak…
-What's he doing?

622
00:25:43,308 --> 00:25:45,210
He has no time to fool around.

623
00:25:45,277 --> 00:25:47,779
-Fabri is fooling around.
-He has no time.

624
00:25:47,846 --> 00:25:50,549
You don't see many people
fooling around on the show.

625
00:25:51,416 --> 00:25:53,752
-He grabs the mackerel.
-Finally, the mackerel.

626
00:25:54,386 --> 00:25:55,720
TRYING TO CUT IT

627
00:25:55,787 --> 00:25:56,821
The mackerel.

628
00:25:56,888 --> 00:26:00,525
Fabri hasn't begun the mackerel confit.
He'll put it in the oil soon.

629
00:26:00,592 --> 00:26:02,894
The moment it sizzles,
it's not confit anymore.

630
00:26:02,961 --> 00:26:04,629
That's just a deep-fry.

631
00:26:05,196 --> 00:26:07,699
-Seven minutes.
-The confit.

632
00:26:08,266 --> 00:26:10,735
WILL THE MACKEREL CONFIT
BE A SUCCESS?

633
00:26:10,802 --> 00:26:12,771
-The confit.
-I'm nervous.

634
00:26:12,837 --> 00:26:14,706
-What's he doing?
-He's putting it into the oil?

635
00:26:14,773 --> 00:26:16,341
Hey, he did it.

636
00:26:16,408 --> 00:26:18,410
He has to cook it for a long time
over low heat.

637
00:26:18,476 --> 00:26:20,312
AMAZED

638
00:26:20,378 --> 00:26:22,280
Wouldn't that turn out too fishy?

639
00:26:22,347 --> 00:26:23,548
-I thought so.
-It's…

640
00:26:23,615 --> 00:26:25,884
-But he likes that fermented taste.
-Hey, I'm sorry,

641
00:26:25,951 --> 00:26:27,886
but I like the funky taste,
not the fishy taste.

642
00:26:27,953 --> 00:26:31,089
-I have a feeling it'll be fishy.
-It looks fishy.

643
00:26:31,156 --> 00:26:32,724
<i>Fishy</i>

644
00:26:32,791 --> 00:26:33,792
"Fishy"?

645
00:26:33,858 --> 00:26:36,161
HE LOVES IT

646
00:26:36,728 --> 00:26:38,563
He's making the dumpling skin.

647
00:26:38,630 --> 00:26:40,031
10. ROLL OUT
THE FRESH PASTA DOUGH

648
00:26:40,098 --> 00:26:44,002
I didn't think he'd make dumpling skin
from scratch in this short while.

649
00:26:45,170 --> 00:26:47,973
-He should've made ravioli dough.
-It looks too…

650
00:26:48,039 --> 00:26:50,942
-It's too dry and firm.
-It's too dry.

651
00:26:51,009 --> 00:26:53,578
-But raviolis are very thin.
-Yes.

652
00:26:53,645 --> 00:26:56,181
-Is that okay?
-It's fine.

653
00:26:56,247 --> 00:26:57,682
He'll have to do that for a while.

654
00:26:57,749 --> 00:26:59,985
Sung-jun, your dough looks too thick.

655
00:27:00,051 --> 00:27:02,020
But I like that orange color.

656
00:27:02,087 --> 00:27:04,389
Yes, the color looks great. It's a pass.

657
00:27:05,256 --> 00:27:06,257
SIGH

658
00:27:07,325 --> 00:27:10,095
He must be flushed. I can hear him sigh.

659
00:27:10,729 --> 00:27:14,232
HE ROLLS OUT THE DOUGH
WHILE BREATHING HEAVILY

660
00:27:14,799 --> 00:27:16,835
HE FINALLY FINISHES
ROLLING IT OUT

661
00:27:17,636 --> 00:27:20,372
But this is…

662
00:27:20,438 --> 00:27:21,673
It's…

663
00:27:21,740 --> 00:27:23,775
You have seven minutes left!

664
00:27:24,476 --> 00:27:26,578
Seven minutes? Already?

665
00:27:27,145 --> 00:27:28,913
SPEEDING UP

666
00:27:28,980 --> 00:27:30,181
5. ADD CHOPPED
CHEONGYANG PEPPER AND SALT

667
00:27:30,248 --> 00:27:31,483
TO HALLABONG, CAPER,
AND CHERRY TOMATO MIX

668
00:27:32,083 --> 00:27:33,652
PREPARING ARUGULA

669
00:27:34,219 --> 00:27:35,654
Oh, no.

670
00:27:36,388 --> 00:27:37,589
I'm in trouble.

671
00:27:38,590 --> 00:27:41,626
PREPARING GREEN ONION TOO

672
00:27:41,693 --> 00:27:43,995
Man, I'm in trouble.

673
00:27:44,863 --> 00:27:47,198
All right. Hurry up, now.

674
00:27:47,265 --> 00:27:48,400
Okay.

675
00:27:48,466 --> 00:27:50,468
Gosh. One second.

676
00:27:51,102 --> 00:27:52,871
NO MATTER HOW MUCH TROUBLE
HE'S IN,

677
00:27:52,937 --> 00:27:54,806
MR. MICHELIN-STAR SLOW
STAYS DELICATE

678
00:27:55,373 --> 00:27:57,942
DONE WITH ARUGULA
AND GREEN ONION

679
00:27:58,009 --> 00:28:00,612
-You have six minutes left.
-Six minutes!

680
00:28:01,279 --> 00:28:03,281
11. PUT DUMPLING FILLING
ON THE PASTA DOUGH

681
00:28:03,348 --> 00:28:05,417
Sung-jun, what are you up to?

682
00:28:05,483 --> 00:28:07,285
I have to make the dumpling.

683
00:28:07,352 --> 00:28:09,220
He just put the filling on the dough.

684
00:28:09,287 --> 00:28:12,057
-Will it cook fully in six minutes?
-Is he making the dumpling?

685
00:28:12,691 --> 00:28:14,959
-The skin…
-It looks thick.

686
00:28:15,026 --> 00:28:16,194
That looks too thick.

687
00:28:16,261 --> 00:28:17,996
You can almost use it
as a blanket in winter.

688
00:28:18,563 --> 00:28:20,031
It's like a blanket.

689
00:28:20,098 --> 00:28:22,167
-It looks warm.
-Yes.

690
00:28:23,334 --> 00:28:26,371
The problem is that it's too thick
and may not cook thoroughly.

691
00:28:26,438 --> 00:28:28,540
He's shaping it like agnolotti.

692
00:28:28,606 --> 00:28:31,042
He may end up eating uncooked pasta dough.

693
00:28:31,109 --> 00:28:32,677
He's fighting against time.

694
00:28:33,511 --> 00:28:35,680
-Will it get cooked?
-Will the dough get cooked?

695
00:28:35,747 --> 00:28:38,183
-He's making the flower.
-Hey!

696
00:28:38,249 --> 00:28:39,484
It's a flower!

697
00:28:39,551 --> 00:28:42,320
-No way!
-It's a flower!

698
00:28:42,387 --> 00:28:43,621
He's making the flower.

699
00:28:44,322 --> 00:28:46,024
A ROUND OF APPLAUSE

700
00:28:46,091 --> 00:28:47,792
-No way.
-He made a flower.

701
00:28:47,859 --> 00:28:50,128
-It just has to cook thoroughly.
-Will it get cooked?

702
00:28:50,195 --> 00:28:52,897
-The thing is, it's too big.
-It is. I doubt it'd get cooked.

703
00:28:52,964 --> 00:28:55,467
-What if it doesn't…
-Are you boiling it?

704
00:28:55,533 --> 00:28:58,937
Myung-soo is in danger
of eating raw pasta dough and mackerel.

705
00:28:59,003 --> 00:29:00,271
I'm a cold-hearted guy.

706
00:29:00,338 --> 00:29:02,340
I even tell my family
something's bad if it is.

707
00:29:02,407 --> 00:29:03,675
I'm that cold-hearted.

708
00:29:04,242 --> 00:29:07,479
6. POUR BOILED POLLACK AND RADISH
INTO A STRAINER TO GET JUST THE SOUP

709
00:29:08,847 --> 00:29:11,616
PRECIOUS SOUP

710
00:29:12,117 --> 00:29:14,119
ADDING WATER

711
00:29:14,185 --> 00:29:16,020
HE BEGINS TO MAKE THE SAUCE

712
00:29:16,454 --> 00:29:18,490
7. GRIND RADISH, TOFU, SALT
AND SESAME OIL TO MAKE SAUCE

713
00:29:18,556 --> 00:29:20,058
-What's that? Soft tofu?
-Soft tofu.

714
00:29:20,125 --> 00:29:22,026
-Sesame oil.
-Sesame oil.

715
00:29:23,661 --> 00:29:26,064
DONE WITH THE SAUCE

716
00:29:28,166 --> 00:29:31,236
-He's using <i>tteokbokki </i>rice cake.
-Rice cake for <i>tteokbokki</i>?

717
00:29:31,302 --> 00:29:33,037
8. CHOP TTEOKBOKKI RICE CAKE,

718
00:29:33,104 --> 00:29:35,406
THROW INTO THE POLLACK SOUP
AND SAUTÉ

719
00:29:35,473 --> 00:29:38,476
Sung-ju, we have five minutes left.

720
00:29:38,543 --> 00:29:40,712
Let me go out to the field.

721
00:29:40,779 --> 00:29:43,782
Which one of them will become
the true Italian chef?

722
00:29:43,848 --> 00:29:45,350
Who'll be the Italian chef?

723
00:29:45,416 --> 00:29:49,821
I'm not sure
if the flower will get fully cooked.

724
00:29:49,888 --> 00:29:52,090
This mackerel is just lying here.

725
00:29:52,157 --> 00:29:53,892
Isn't the heat too low?

726
00:29:53,958 --> 00:29:55,693
No, there's no heat.

727
00:29:55,760 --> 00:29:56,795
-Nothing.
-There's no heat.

728
00:29:56,861 --> 00:29:58,863
Did you just throw it into hot oil?

729
00:29:58,930 --> 00:30:00,732
Yes, you're right.

730
00:30:00,799 --> 00:30:03,968
-Do I have to eat raw food today?
-It's yes versus yes.

731
00:30:04,035 --> 00:30:06,337
-All right. The <i>bugeoguk</i>!
-The <i>bugeoguk</i>!

732
00:30:06,404 --> 00:30:08,640
-The <i>bugeoguk</i>!
-They have 4 minutes and 18 seconds left.

733
00:30:08,706 --> 00:30:10,542
Let me try the soup.

734
00:30:10,608 --> 00:30:13,178
-Do you think Myung-soo will like it?
-What's it like?

735
00:30:13,244 --> 00:30:16,214
-Does it smell funky?
-Does it smell funky?

736
00:30:16,281 --> 00:30:17,782
Does it smell funky?

737
00:30:17,849 --> 00:30:19,684
It's not too strong yet.

738
00:30:19,751 --> 00:30:22,287
-Dried seafood?
-It's not too strong yet.

739
00:30:22,353 --> 00:30:24,289
It has to boil down some more.

740
00:30:24,355 --> 00:30:26,024
-It's not rich yet.
-It's not.

741
00:30:26,090 --> 00:30:27,192
Is it not so funky yet?

742
00:30:27,258 --> 00:30:30,094
-If it is, we should smell it by now.
-We can't smell it yet.

743
00:30:30,161 --> 00:30:32,397
-I can't smell anything.
-It hasn't reached us.

744
00:30:32,463 --> 00:30:34,866
-It just smells like a studio.
-Yes.

745
00:30:34,933 --> 00:30:38,102
-Fabri, take a look at the mackerel.
-It's fine.

746
00:30:38,169 --> 00:30:39,170
Is it okay?

747
00:30:39,237 --> 00:30:40,538
CHECKING THE MACKEREL

748
00:30:41,039 --> 00:30:42,240
Gosh.

749
00:30:43,942 --> 00:30:47,812
-Did you pull the mackerel out already?
-Yes!

750
00:30:47,879 --> 00:30:50,048
He pulled it out.

751
00:30:50,114 --> 00:30:52,317
-Already?
-He pulled it out.

752
00:30:52,383 --> 00:30:53,985
It's so not cooked.

753
00:30:54,052 --> 00:30:56,221
The mackerel is so not cooked!

754
00:30:56,287 --> 00:30:58,756
-Torch.
-He pulled it out.

755
00:30:58,823 --> 00:31:00,725
-He's using a torch.
-I can smell something.

756
00:31:00,792 --> 00:31:04,362
-He grabbed a torch.
-This was it!

757
00:31:04,429 --> 00:31:06,965
-Just like that?
-This was it!

758
00:31:07,031 --> 00:31:08,399
-He's using a torch.
-I knew it.

759
00:31:08,466 --> 00:31:10,235
That'll make a rich and funky taste.

760
00:31:10,301 --> 00:31:11,870
-He's using a torch!
-I knew it.

761
00:31:11,936 --> 00:31:13,504
That'll make a rich and funky taste.

762
00:31:14,706 --> 00:31:16,107
It'll taste richer if it's broiled.

763
00:31:16,174 --> 00:31:19,744
He's now broiling the mackerel skin.

764
00:31:19,811 --> 00:31:23,715
-Broil it some more! Make it funkier!
-He wants you to broil it even more!

765
00:31:23,781 --> 00:31:25,016
Please make it funky.

766
00:31:25,083 --> 00:31:27,051
-All right.
-Funky?

767
00:31:27,118 --> 00:31:30,021
You have 2 minutes and 30 seconds left.
Let me taste it again.

768
00:31:30,088 --> 00:31:31,723
This is Sung-jun's <i>bugeoguk</i>.

769
00:31:33,825 --> 00:31:36,594
Does it taste funky?

770
00:31:36,661 --> 00:31:38,997
Does it taste funky?

771
00:31:39,898 --> 00:31:43,434
It tastes totally funky!

772
00:31:43,501 --> 00:31:44,736
CELEBRATING THE FUNKINESS

773
00:31:44,802 --> 00:31:46,437
-Funkiness!
-It boiled down.

774
00:31:46,504 --> 00:31:47,639
It's delicious.

775
00:31:47,705 --> 00:31:50,074
-It's delicious.
-Isn't it good?

776
00:31:50,141 --> 00:31:52,543
It's funky and has that umami.

777
00:31:52,610 --> 00:31:53,978
I like it.

778
00:31:54,045 --> 00:31:57,215
We're starting to smell the funkiness.

779
00:31:57,282 --> 00:31:59,083
-Can you smell it? It's funky.
-Yes, I can.

780
00:31:59,150 --> 00:32:00,518
-I can smell it.
-Yes.

781
00:32:00,585 --> 00:32:02,353
It smells like a <i>bugeoguk </i>restaurant!

782
00:32:02,420 --> 00:32:05,089
-So this is what you like.
-Yes.

783
00:32:05,690 --> 00:32:07,525
9. MIX STIR-FRIED RICE CAKE,
BLACK PEPPER,

784
00:32:07,592 --> 00:32:09,227
AND OLIVE OIL TO MAKE SALAD

785
00:32:09,294 --> 00:32:11,796
It's all right. You can take your time.

786
00:32:12,363 --> 00:32:14,933
HE GETS THE DRIED POLLACK
FROM THE OVEN

787
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:20,605
10. JULIENNE ROASTED
DRIED POLLACK

788
00:32:21,172 --> 00:32:23,274
HE BEGINS BY SERVING THE SAUCE

789
00:32:24,175 --> 00:32:25,176
POURING IT CAREFULLY

790
00:32:25,243 --> 00:32:27,745
Fabri, what are you serving?

791
00:32:27,812 --> 00:32:29,981
-This is ra-to.
-You have a mi

792
00:32:30,048 --> 00:32:33,351
-Hurry up! Stop talking.
-You're running out of time!

793
00:32:33,418 --> 00:32:35,687
Please move as you talk.

794
00:32:35,753 --> 00:32:38,089
Let me try the soft tofu dressing.

795
00:32:38,156 --> 00:32:40,258
-It has to be funkier.
-They have one minute!

796
00:32:40,325 --> 00:32:45,763
Is the sauce smooth?

797
00:32:45,830 --> 00:32:48,199
-We're in Italy.
-Italy!

798
00:32:48,266 --> 00:32:49,734
We're in Italy.

799
00:32:49,801 --> 00:32:52,203
<i>Señorita!</i>

800
00:32:52,270 --> 00:32:53,304
Is that not it?

801
00:32:53,371 --> 00:32:55,473
-That's Spanish.
-I'm sorry.

802
00:32:56,040 --> 00:32:57,675
12. ADD STARCH WATER TO BUGEOGUK

803
00:32:57,742 --> 00:32:59,444
He's adding starch water.

804
00:33:01,980 --> 00:33:03,114
HE STRAINS THE SOUP RIGHT AWAY

805
00:33:03,181 --> 00:33:05,116
What's that? Are you using just the soup?

806
00:33:05,183 --> 00:33:07,318
-Yes.
-He's using just the soup!

807
00:33:07,385 --> 00:33:08,853
He'll use it like sauce.

808
00:33:08,920 --> 00:33:11,255
-To make a clean taste.
-Yes, he'll throw these out.

809
00:33:12,790 --> 00:33:17,428
HE GETS THE CABBAGE
AND BEGINS TO SERVE THE FOOD

810
00:33:17,495 --> 00:33:19,530
Fabri began serving his dish.

811
00:33:20,932 --> 00:33:23,634
My gosh, Fabri, this is so good.

812
00:33:23,701 --> 00:33:25,169
The fish he roasted in the oven.

813
00:33:25,236 --> 00:33:26,738
-Thirty seconds!
-You have thirty seconds.

814
00:33:26,804 --> 00:33:28,639
-Thirty seconds!
-Thirty seconds.

815
00:33:28,706 --> 00:33:30,742
-Thirty seconds!
-Thirty seconds.

816
00:33:30,808 --> 00:33:35,413
I hope this is fully cooked.
The flower is the biggest issue.

817
00:33:35,480 --> 00:33:38,983
The flower. What will you do?
The petals are about to fall apart.

818
00:33:39,050 --> 00:33:40,818
-What now?
-Hey.

819
00:33:40,885 --> 00:33:42,453
You have to finish up.

820
00:33:43,588 --> 00:33:45,156
Come on.

821
00:33:45,223 --> 00:33:46,657
Twelve seconds.

822
00:33:46,724 --> 00:33:48,359
-It looks pretty.
-Ten.

823
00:33:48,426 --> 00:33:50,695
-Nine. Eight.
-Eight. Seven.

824
00:33:50,762 --> 00:33:54,032
-Six. Five. Four.
-Oh, no. Pull it out already.

825
00:33:54,098 --> 00:33:57,201
-Six. Five. Four.
-Six. Five. Four.

826
00:33:57,268 --> 00:33:59,570
-My gosh.
-Three. Two.

827
00:33:59,637 --> 00:34:02,306
-Fabri is done.
-Fabri finished up.

828
00:34:02,373 --> 00:34:04,842
SUNG-JUN SERVES THE FLOWER TOO

829
00:34:04,909 --> 00:34:07,845
-Is that <i>hallabong</i>?
-I hope it's cooked.

830
00:34:07,912 --> 00:34:09,514
Isn't that a <i>hallabong</i>?

831
00:34:09,580 --> 00:34:12,517
-Let's climb Halla Mountain.
-<i>Hallabong</i>?

832
00:34:12,583 --> 00:34:15,119
Sung-jun is done. Please ring the bell.

833
00:34:15,186 --> 00:34:16,754
He's done.

834
00:34:16,821 --> 00:34:19,657
-Chef Sung-jun is done too.
-It looks cooked.

835
00:34:19,724 --> 00:34:21,759
This feels really nice.

836
00:34:22,360 --> 00:34:23,861
THE RETURN MATCH ENDS

837
00:34:23,928 --> 00:34:29,167
They both finished the order
for Grandpa Myung-soo wants pics.

838
00:34:29,233 --> 00:34:31,135
You haven't tried it yet,

839
00:34:31,202 --> 00:34:33,938
but which one of these
do you want to take pictures of?

840
00:34:34,005 --> 00:34:35,673
-They both have a certain appeal.
-They do.

841
00:34:35,740 --> 00:34:36,874
I want to capture both.

842
00:34:36,941 --> 00:34:39,444
-It looks good.
-I want pictures for both.

843
00:34:39,510 --> 00:34:42,580
The kitchen is usually closed off
at restaurants, right?

844
00:34:42,647 --> 00:34:43,815
But we're sitting here and watching.

845
00:34:43,881 --> 00:34:46,184
I was very grateful and honored

846
00:34:46,250 --> 00:34:48,486
as I watched them cook for me.

847
00:34:48,553 --> 00:34:51,189
Why do you talk like that
if you could talk so sweetly?

848
00:34:51,255 --> 00:34:53,524
I need to make a living.

849
00:34:53,591 --> 00:34:55,259
I need to be harsh to make a living.

850
00:34:55,326 --> 00:34:57,929
And now, his cold yet impartial review is
coming right up.

851
00:34:59,197 --> 00:35:02,800
MACKEREL SLOWLY COOKED
IN LOW-TEMPERATURE OIL

852
00:35:03,734 --> 00:35:08,239
POLLACK, RICE CAKE, TOMATO
PANZANELLA AND SOFT TOFU SAUCE

853
00:35:10,341 --> 00:35:13,911
CHEF FABRI'S REVENGE MACKEREL

854
00:35:13,978 --> 00:35:15,179
Mmm.

855
00:35:15,246 --> 00:35:17,515
Smell it and see if it's funky.

856
00:35:17,582 --> 00:35:20,384
-I can smell it already.
-Already?

857
00:35:20,451 --> 00:35:25,723
We didn't think he'd use a torch
to broil the mackerel.

858
00:35:25,790 --> 00:35:27,758
The smell is

859
00:35:27,825 --> 00:35:30,928
just the right amount of funkiness.

860
00:35:30,995 --> 00:35:32,763
It's not too much. And oddly,

861
00:35:32,830 --> 00:35:35,266
it doesn't smell burnt or fishy.

862
00:35:35,333 --> 00:35:37,635
-I have to take a picture. It's pretty.
-Please take one.

863
00:35:37,702 --> 00:35:42,106
You can decide later if you want
to send it to your daughter or not.

864
00:35:42,173 --> 00:35:43,908
-I like it.
-It's his picture.

865
00:35:43,975 --> 00:35:47,278
-Both dishes look great.
-I don't think it'll look delicious.

866
00:35:48,446 --> 00:35:50,748
-I like it. I took pictures.
-Okay, good.

867
00:35:50,815 --> 00:35:52,850
-It looks pretty.
-It does.

868
00:35:52,917 --> 00:35:54,852
He'll have to see if it was cooked well.

869
00:35:54,919 --> 00:35:57,221
Fabri has great presentation skills.

870
00:35:57,288 --> 00:35:59,223
How should I eat this?

871
00:35:59,290 --> 00:36:01,826
Try the mackerel and the sauce first.

872
00:36:01,893 --> 00:36:06,797
Then you can try the salad as a refresher.

873
00:36:06,864 --> 00:36:11,536
I think everything goes well together.

874
00:36:12,136 --> 00:36:15,339
But I never eat mackerel skin.

875
00:36:15,406 --> 00:36:20,311
-Peel it off.
-It's easy to peel it off, actually.

876
00:36:20,378 --> 00:36:22,113
-Myung-soo is so…
-Try some.

877
00:36:22,180 --> 00:36:23,814
I can peel it.

878
00:36:23,881 --> 00:36:25,516
Hey, this guy.

879
00:36:25,583 --> 00:36:27,752
Look how easy it was to peel it off.

880
00:36:27,818 --> 00:36:30,154
-He peeled it off right away.
-Look at this.

881
00:36:30,221 --> 00:36:31,856
I was going to get mad
if it didn't peel off.

882
00:36:31,923 --> 00:36:33,824
But it came off at once.

883
00:36:33,891 --> 00:36:36,294
He's so skillful.

884
00:36:36,360 --> 00:36:39,564
I don't eat the skin,
so it felt great to peel it off easily.

885
00:36:39,630 --> 00:36:42,266
-Everything is good thus far.
-He's doing great so far.

886
00:36:42,333 --> 00:36:45,069
I have to dip it in the sauce, right?

887
00:36:45,136 --> 00:36:47,138
-Let me try just the mackerel.
-Okay.

888
00:36:47,838 --> 00:36:50,508
-It looks fully cooked, right?
-Yes.

889
00:36:51,809 --> 00:36:53,611
-I wonder.
-He tries the mackerel.

890
00:36:53,678 --> 00:36:57,081
-Will it taste funky or just fishy?
-Right.

891
00:36:57,148 --> 00:37:00,451
-He'll give an objective review. Hey!
-What is it?

892
00:37:01,018 --> 00:37:02,486
-Hey!
-What is it?

893
00:37:02,553 --> 00:37:04,188
-It must be fishy.
-What is it?

894
00:37:04,255 --> 00:37:05,656
What do you mean by that?

895
00:37:05,723 --> 00:37:07,658
He just slammed the fork on the table.

896
00:37:07,725 --> 00:37:09,026
-What do you mean?
-What is it?

897
00:37:09,093 --> 00:37:11,429
-Is it that good?
-What is it?

898
00:37:12,663 --> 00:37:15,299
HE WAS MOVED

899
00:37:16,400 --> 00:37:18,169
You made my heart drop.

900
00:37:18,236 --> 00:37:19,670
-It doesn't smell fishy at all.
-Not at all?

901
00:37:19,737 --> 00:37:21,305
-It tastes funky.
-It must've been good.

902
00:37:21,372 --> 00:37:23,407
-It's nicely funky.
-I thought it'd be fishy.

903
00:37:23,474 --> 00:37:25,743
I've never had
such a pleasantly funky mackerel.

904
00:37:25,810 --> 00:37:27,712
-It's funky yet delicious.
-I see.

905
00:37:27,778 --> 00:37:30,548
Then the scent
of the fillet follows right away.

906
00:37:30,615 --> 00:37:33,517
Lastly, the smooth sauce. It's delicious.

907
00:37:33,584 --> 00:37:34,885
It's really good.

908
00:37:34,952 --> 00:37:39,123
He seasoned the mackerel, right?
So I got a taste of that salty meat first.

909
00:37:39,190 --> 00:37:40,291
Is this cream sauce?

910
00:37:40,358 --> 00:37:42,326
<i>It's a mix of soft tofu and radish.</i>

911
00:37:42,393 --> 00:37:44,729
<i>So I called it ra-to sauce.</i>

912
00:37:44,795 --> 00:37:46,530
-Ra-to.
-Ra-to sauce.

913
00:37:46,597 --> 00:37:49,367
The mackerel tastes Korean.
It's just seasoned mackerel.

914
00:37:49,433 --> 00:37:53,037
But this sauce
completely changes everything.

915
00:37:53,104 --> 00:37:54,372
It's amazing.

916
00:37:55,172 --> 00:37:57,208
He must be a famous man.

917
00:37:57,275 --> 00:37:59,577
Fabri wasn't someone
who'd lose that easily.

918
00:37:59,644 --> 00:38:03,247
I had the meat, so my mouth might smell.
So next, the rice cake.

919
00:38:03,314 --> 00:38:06,550
-<i>Panzanella</i>. It's a type of salad.
-That one.

920
00:38:07,285 --> 00:38:09,854
He removed the seeds from the tomatoes.

921
00:38:09,920 --> 00:38:11,889
-What is it?
-What's wrong?

922
00:38:11,956 --> 00:38:13,591
This time, are you mad?

923
00:38:13,658 --> 00:38:15,293
How was the <i>panzanella</i>?

924
00:38:15,359 --> 00:38:16,394
All right!

925
00:38:16,961 --> 00:38:18,095
Fabri!

926
00:38:18,162 --> 00:38:19,397
APPLAUDED TWICE

927
00:38:19,463 --> 00:38:20,898
The rice cake and…

928
00:38:20,965 --> 00:38:23,601
Did you put in chopped dried pollack?

929
00:38:23,668 --> 00:38:25,169
It's the highlight.

930
00:38:25,236 --> 00:38:26,437
It's amazing.

931
00:38:26,504 --> 00:38:29,206
-The dried pollack is the highlight.
-How did he come up with that?

932
00:38:29,273 --> 00:38:32,076
It's tough for salad to taste funky.

933
00:38:32,143 --> 00:38:33,210
-It's fresh.
-Yes.

934
00:38:33,277 --> 00:38:35,046
But he mixed dried pollack into the salad.

935
00:38:35,112 --> 00:38:37,815
-Never seen him enjoying food so much.
-Me either.

936
00:38:37,882 --> 00:38:40,918
The texture of the tomato, the rice cake,

937
00:38:40,985 --> 00:38:43,788
and dried pollack are all different.

938
00:38:43,854 --> 00:38:46,257
-Yes.
-It adds fun into the experience.

939
00:38:46,324 --> 00:38:49,927
You can try many different textures.

940
00:38:49,994 --> 00:38:53,030
It was a great idea
to add dried pollack into this.

941
00:38:53,097 --> 00:38:56,233
-That was the highlight.
-He takes another bite.

942
00:38:56,300 --> 00:38:58,169
Let's give it up for Fabri again!

943
00:38:58,235 --> 00:39:02,940
-I thought Myung-soo would yell at him.
-Fabri wasn't someone who would lose.

944
00:39:03,007 --> 00:39:04,075
I never lie.

945
00:39:04,141 --> 00:39:06,644
Next, Chef Sung-jun's dish.

946
00:39:06,711 --> 00:39:10,214
<i>I Came to Make Flower Pasta</i>

947
00:39:11,682 --> 00:39:15,052
PASTA DUMPLING
SHAPED LIKE A FLOWER

948
00:39:17,355 --> 00:39:21,359
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN'S
I CAME TO MAKE FLOWER PASTA

949
00:39:21,425 --> 00:39:22,827
-This one is…
-Take a picture.

950
00:39:22,893 --> 00:39:25,696
I've never seen anything like this.
Who would do this?

951
00:39:25,763 --> 00:39:28,065
Isn't the flower bud a bit too fat?

952
00:39:29,300 --> 00:39:32,103
-It's way too thick.
-It's a bit much for me.

953
00:39:32,169 --> 00:39:34,271
-It's obese.
-Yes, an obese flower.

954
00:39:34,338 --> 00:39:36,741
-It's like <i>hallabong </i>from Jeju.
-Yes, rather.

955
00:39:36,807 --> 00:39:39,910
<i>I Came to Make Hallabong Pasta</i>

956
00:39:39,977 --> 00:39:41,312
He should've done that.

957
00:39:41,379 --> 00:39:45,082
That rhythm is the old children's song,
not Jisoo's version.

958
00:39:46,317 --> 00:39:49,420
<i>I Came to Make Hallabong Pasta</i>

959
00:39:49,487 --> 00:39:51,589
That's not it.

960
00:39:51,655 --> 00:39:53,124
Gosh, such an old man.

961
00:39:53,691 --> 00:39:55,393
OLD MAN!

962
00:39:55,960 --> 00:39:57,661
He's taking a picture.

963
00:39:57,728 --> 00:39:59,196
It looks so pretty, though.

964
00:39:59,263 --> 00:40:01,532
I love how he had this idea.

965
00:40:01,599 --> 00:40:05,069
It's amazing how he made this
in just 15 minutes.

966
00:40:05,136 --> 00:40:07,104
-I have to try the soup first.
-The soup.

967
00:40:07,171 --> 00:40:08,939
The soup is half of the dish.

968
00:40:09,006 --> 00:40:11,275
-Yes.
-If the soup is good, everything is fine.

969
00:40:11,342 --> 00:40:13,711
-The soup first.
-Yes, it's about the soup.

970
00:40:13,778 --> 00:40:15,813
What did you put into this?
Frozen pollack…

971
00:40:15,880 --> 00:40:19,383
<i>-Dried pollack.</i>
<i>-Dried pollack, radish, and cabbage.</i>

972
00:40:19,450 --> 00:40:22,353
<i>It was a shame to see</i>
<i>how he pulled out the solid ingredients.</i>

973
00:40:22,420 --> 00:40:24,255
-It's pretty much the extract.
-The soup.

974
00:40:24,889 --> 00:40:26,624
And? How's the soup?

975
00:40:28,359 --> 00:40:30,394
-What is it?
-What's with him?

976
00:40:30,461 --> 00:40:32,496
What is it? How's the soup? Is it too hot?

977
00:40:32,563 --> 00:40:34,432
What is it? How's the soup?

978
00:40:34,498 --> 00:40:36,000
Is it too hot?

979
00:40:36,066 --> 00:40:38,936
-It's so good.
-It's so good.

980
00:40:39,003 --> 00:40:41,338
-It's so good.
-It's so good.

981
00:40:41,405 --> 00:40:43,073
He's a magician.

982
00:40:43,140 --> 00:40:45,009
It tastes so funky.

983
00:40:45,075 --> 00:40:48,879
It's like <i>bugeoguk </i>extract.

984
00:40:48,946 --> 00:40:51,816
It almost feels medicinal.

985
00:40:51,882 --> 00:40:55,286
-It's as if he made it into medicine.
-Like medicine?

986
00:40:55,352 --> 00:40:58,055
-How did he make this?
-He boiled it down like medicine.

987
00:40:58,122 --> 00:40:59,924
-Like oriental medicine?
-The soup?

988
00:40:59,990 --> 00:41:01,091
My gosh.

989
00:41:01,659 --> 00:41:03,127
It's also sweet, thanks to the cabbage.

990
00:41:03,194 --> 00:41:05,696
-I see.
-Then I can smell the dried pollack.

991
00:41:05,763 --> 00:41:09,266
-He's sipping it again.
-I can chug just the soup right now.

992
00:41:09,333 --> 00:41:10,968
-But the problem is…
-The problem is…

993
00:41:11,035 --> 00:41:13,103
-It looks pretty heavy.
-The flower bud.

994
00:41:13,170 --> 00:41:15,506
-Cut it.
-I hope it's cooked on the inside.

995
00:41:15,573 --> 00:41:19,477
-We're dying to know too.
-I hope it's not raw dough.

996
00:41:19,543 --> 00:41:20,945
The soup was so good.

997
00:41:21,912 --> 00:41:23,414
He's cutting it.

998
00:41:23,481 --> 00:41:25,316
-He's cutting it. Is it cooked?
-It's a bit too heavy.

999
00:41:25,382 --> 00:41:27,585
-It looks…
-Is it too tough?

1000
00:41:27,651 --> 00:41:29,320
I can see something inside.

1001
00:41:29,386 --> 00:41:30,988
-Please cut it apart.
-It's cooked.

1002
00:41:31,055 --> 00:41:33,057
-It's cooked.
-It's cooked.

1003
00:41:33,123 --> 00:41:34,959
It's cooked.

1004
00:41:35,025 --> 00:41:37,228
-My gosh.
-It's cooked.

1005
00:41:37,294 --> 00:41:38,829
All right.

1006
00:41:38,896 --> 00:41:40,898
-It smells good.
-I hope it's cooked well.

1007
00:41:40,965 --> 00:41:43,133
Does it taste funky?

1008
00:41:43,200 --> 00:41:44,301
He takes a bite!

1009
00:41:45,135 --> 00:41:47,771
He can tell if it's cooked or not
as soon as he bites into it.

1010
00:41:47,838 --> 00:41:48,839
The flower pasta!

1011
00:41:48,906 --> 00:41:51,308
-The flower pasta!
-Is it cooked?

1012
00:41:51,909 --> 00:41:54,845
-Myung-soo? Yes, it's cooked.
-It's cooked.

1013
00:41:54,912 --> 00:41:56,780
-It's cooked.
-It is? I'm glad.

1014
00:41:56,847 --> 00:41:58,516
-It looks a bit bland.
-It's cooked.

1015
00:41:58,582 --> 00:42:01,886
But he's not moved.
It's just fully cooked.

1016
00:42:01,952 --> 00:42:04,154
-He put gochujang in it.
-His face looks different.

1017
00:42:04,221 --> 00:42:05,256
It's just cooked.

1018
00:42:05,322 --> 00:42:08,359
-There's too much dough.
-I'm curious.

1019
00:42:08,425 --> 00:42:09,693
What's inside?

1020
00:42:09,760 --> 00:42:12,363
<i>-Scallop and shrimp.</i>
<i>-Scallop, shrimp, tofu,</i>

1021
00:42:12,429 --> 00:42:16,066
-sesame oil, and funky tuna sauce.
-What's wrong?

1022
00:42:16,133 --> 00:42:17,434
I'm so sorry.

1023
00:42:17,501 --> 00:42:20,237
But you were the winner,
so let me try it once again. I'm sorry.

1024
00:42:20,304 --> 00:42:23,007
-He might have missed something.
-I have to try it again.

1025
00:42:23,073 --> 00:42:24,642
-What will he say?
-Tell us what it's like.

1026
00:42:24,708 --> 00:42:26,744
I've always wanted to meet him,

1027
00:42:26,810 --> 00:42:28,612
so this is a bit awkward.

1028
00:42:28,679 --> 00:42:30,014
HIS REVIEW WAS ALSO UNCERTAIN

1029
00:42:30,080 --> 00:42:32,683
-That's how he feels.
-Something must be odd.

1030
00:42:32,750 --> 00:42:35,185
-I wanted to meet you.
-He wanted to meet him.

1031
00:42:35,252 --> 00:42:37,922
-And he loved Myung-soo.
-He has to be fair and square.

1032
00:42:37,988 --> 00:42:41,425
It could've been a flavor
he didn't really prefer.

1033
00:42:41,492 --> 00:42:43,794
The scallop filling tastes delicious,

1034
00:42:43,861 --> 00:42:46,297
and the soup is almost medicinal.

1035
00:42:46,363 --> 00:42:48,299
-But?
-There's too much dough.

1036
00:42:48,365 --> 00:42:49,800
I knew it.

1037
00:42:49,867 --> 00:42:52,469
-It was too thick.
-He added too much flour.

1038
00:42:52,536 --> 00:42:54,905
Because of the dough's texture,

1039
00:42:54,972 --> 00:42:57,841
-it's tough to taste the filling.
-I see.

1040
00:42:57,908 --> 00:43:00,277
That's what I want to say.

1041
00:43:00,344 --> 00:43:01,812
-It was too thick.
-But the soup is…

1042
00:43:01,879 --> 00:43:03,547
-The soup was so good.
-Anyone could see it.

1043
00:43:03,614 --> 00:43:05,115
It should've gone on a diet.

1044
00:43:05,182 --> 00:43:07,551
But he loves the soup so much.

1045
00:43:07,618 --> 00:43:09,520
This soup is almost medicinal.

1046
00:43:09,587 --> 00:43:11,388
First, Fabri's dish.

1047
00:43:11,455 --> 00:43:14,124
Let's try Revenge Mackerel.

1048
00:43:14,692 --> 00:43:16,093
THEY WERE CURIOUS
ABOUT THE MACKEREL CONFIT

1049
00:43:16,160 --> 00:43:17,161
What will it be like?

1050
00:43:17,227 --> 00:43:19,096
The salad has a variety of textures.

1051
00:43:19,163 --> 00:43:21,265
I've never had salad like it. It's good.

1052
00:43:21,332 --> 00:43:24,001
We usually roast mackerels, don't we?

1053
00:43:24,068 --> 00:43:26,570
-So we end up losing some juice.
-That's right.

1054
00:43:26,637 --> 00:43:29,239
<i>But this way of cooking</i>
<i>captured the juice all inside.</i>

1055
00:43:29,306 --> 00:43:33,310
The more you chew,
the more you can taste the funky mackerel.

1056
00:43:33,377 --> 00:43:36,113
-Yes, it's completely funky.
-Isn't it?

1057
00:43:36,180 --> 00:43:38,916
It seemed like
he wasn't concerned about the fish.

1058
00:43:38,983 --> 00:43:40,951
He was busy roasting dried pollack

1059
00:43:41,018 --> 00:43:45,756
and pulling out tomato seeds,
so I wondered why he was doing that.

1060
00:43:45,823 --> 00:43:47,725
I thought he wasn't thinking straight.

1061
00:43:47,791 --> 00:43:49,026
AMAZED

1062
00:43:49,093 --> 00:43:50,194
But that was the kick.

1063
00:43:50,260 --> 00:43:52,296
He kept roasting

1064
00:43:52,363 --> 00:43:55,232
-the dried pollack in the pan, right?
-That was the key.

1065
00:43:55,299 --> 00:43:57,635
That crunchy fish is the highlight.

1066
00:43:57,701 --> 00:43:59,937
Yes, I loved the mix of textures.

1067
00:44:00,004 --> 00:44:02,339
-Sung-jun, have you tried it? How was it?
-Yes.

1068
00:44:02,406 --> 00:44:03,574
It was very delicious.

1069
00:44:03,641 --> 00:44:07,845
I thought he put together a dish
with strong Korean flavors.

1070
00:44:07,911 --> 00:44:09,179
He's a fake Italian.

1071
00:44:09,246 --> 00:44:10,514
HE WAS JUST LIKE A FAKE ITALIAN

1072
00:44:11,649 --> 00:44:14,385
-So he's a fake Italian.
-He's a fake Italian.

1073
00:44:14,451 --> 00:44:19,056
Next, let's try Chef Sung-jun's
I Came to Make Flower Pasta.

1074
00:44:19,123 --> 00:44:21,959
SLURP

1075
00:44:23,560 --> 00:44:26,263
Nice. He was right.

1076
00:44:26,330 --> 00:44:27,998
-It's a bit spicy too.
-It's almost medicinal.

1077
00:44:28,065 --> 00:44:30,634
-It tastes so healthy.
-Cabbage is good for you.

1078
00:44:30,701 --> 00:44:33,037
It wasn't even greasy.
I love this refreshing taste.

1079
00:44:33,103 --> 00:44:38,275
I understand why you said
you kept chewing on too much dough.

1080
00:44:38,342 --> 00:44:41,345
It's not that the skin is too thick.

1081
00:44:41,412 --> 00:44:43,514
The starch in the filling
blended for too long

1082
00:44:43,580 --> 00:44:45,649
and began to feel like rice cake.

1083
00:44:45,716 --> 00:44:49,753
There's no difference between the skin
and the filling. I think that's why.

1084
00:44:49,820 --> 00:44:52,322
Poong is spot on.

1085
00:44:52,389 --> 00:44:55,559
That was exactly what I was thinking.

1086
00:44:55,626 --> 00:44:59,930
If he had put in egg whites
or less starch,

1087
00:44:59,997 --> 00:45:02,433
it would've had a different texture.

1088
00:45:02,499 --> 00:45:05,202
-Or more tofu.
-I see.

1089
00:45:05,269 --> 00:45:07,471
-And…
-Poong got that.

1090
00:45:07,538 --> 00:45:09,406
That was a sharp review.

1091
00:45:09,473 --> 00:45:12,109
-I can't believe he noticed that.
-He's on fire.

1092
00:45:12,176 --> 00:45:15,179
Poong is about to go in the next round.

1093
00:45:15,245 --> 00:45:17,948
Nam-no, pull it together. You must focus.

1094
00:45:18,015 --> 00:45:19,883
-Please make your decision.
-It's hard.

1095
00:45:19,950 --> 00:45:22,553
Please make your decision.
It's time to decide.

1096
00:45:22,619 --> 00:45:24,888
He was going to berate them,

1097
00:45:24,955 --> 00:45:27,124
-but we didn't hear anything.
-He couldn't do it.

1098
00:45:27,191 --> 00:45:30,094
-Fabri versus Kwon Sung-jun.
-He enjoyed both.

1099
00:45:30,160 --> 00:45:31,662
You have to decide now.

1100
00:45:31,729 --> 00:45:32,796
Press one for Fabri.

1101
00:45:32,863 --> 00:45:34,231
CHEF FABRI'S REVENGE MACKEREL

1102
00:45:34,298 --> 00:45:35,499
Press two for Sung-jun.

1103
00:45:35,566 --> 00:45:36,967
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN'S
I CAME TO MAKE FLOWER PASTA

1104
00:45:37,034 --> 00:45:40,471
I feel so bad. What do I do?
I don't want to be on the show.

1105
00:45:40,537 --> 00:45:41,572
Please make your choice

1106
00:45:41,638 --> 00:45:43,107
and press the button!

1107
00:45:43,173 --> 00:45:45,109
I'm not cut out for this show.

1108
00:45:45,676 --> 00:45:47,644
He pressed the button.

1109
00:45:47,711 --> 00:45:49,580
-He decided.
-Let's check the result.

1110
00:45:49,646 --> 00:45:51,982
Gosh, I feel so bad.

1111
00:45:52,049 --> 00:45:54,184
-So?
-I didn't come here to do this.

1112
00:45:54,251 --> 00:45:58,122
Who did Myung-soo choose? Let's find out.

1113
00:45:58,188 --> 00:46:01,759
-Let's find out.
-Grandpa Myung-soo wants pics.

1114
00:46:01,825 --> 00:46:04,194
Will it be Sung-jun's flower?

1115
00:46:04,261 --> 00:46:06,263
Or is it Fabri's mackerel?

1116
00:46:06,330 --> 00:46:10,200
Will Fabri get his revenge on Sung-jun,

1117
00:46:10,267 --> 00:46:12,770
on the winner of <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>?

1118
00:46:12,836 --> 00:46:15,172
Can Fabri get his revenge?

1119
00:46:15,239 --> 00:46:18,308
Or did Sung-jun seize the victory again?

1120
00:46:19,276 --> 00:46:20,511
Who's the winner?

1121
00:46:20,577 --> 00:46:23,614
FABRI WINS

1122
00:46:24,882 --> 00:46:26,250
-Fabri!
-Fabri!

1123
00:46:27,017 --> 00:46:28,886
Fabri gets his revenge.

1124
00:46:30,554 --> 00:46:32,856
-Congratulations.
-Great job.

1125
00:46:33,857 --> 00:46:36,760
You just won against the winner
of <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.

1126
00:46:36,827 --> 00:46:39,530
The winner of <i>Culinary Class Wars</i> lost.

1127
00:46:39,596 --> 00:46:41,465
I managed to protect

1128
00:46:41,532 --> 00:46:44,301
my pride as an Italian.

1129
00:46:44,368 --> 00:46:47,104
Yes, you saved your Italian pride.

1130
00:46:47,171 --> 00:46:48,172
Thank you.

1131
00:46:48,772 --> 00:46:49,773
He's welling up.

1132
00:46:51,141 --> 00:46:52,810
-Yes, right now.
-This is great.

1133
00:46:52,876 --> 00:46:56,580
He lost by a hair during the skate round.

1134
00:46:56,647 --> 00:46:59,049
<i>But he won against the skate</i>
<i>with this mackerel today.</i>

1135
00:46:59,116 --> 00:47:01,151
Right. He did it with the mackerel.

1136
00:47:01,218 --> 00:47:02,719
Why did you choose him?

1137
00:47:02,786 --> 00:47:06,356
I personally wanted
to befriend Chef Sung-jun.

1138
00:47:06,423 --> 00:47:09,293
-He even said you were his favorite.
-He was a fan.

1139
00:47:09,359 --> 00:47:11,995
-He even shared your quotes.
-But here's the thing.

1140
00:47:12,062 --> 00:47:14,364
Let's not go there.

1141
00:47:14,431 --> 00:47:17,167
I had to make a choice.

1142
00:47:17,234 --> 00:47:18,836
The <i>hallabong </i>was a bit big.

1143
00:47:18,902 --> 00:47:20,604
It was a flower, not <i>hallabong</i>.

1144
00:47:20,671 --> 00:47:21,939
Yes, the flower.

1145
00:47:22,005 --> 00:47:25,342
-It was a bit swollen.
-Swollen?

1146
00:47:25,409 --> 00:47:26,743
-I'm sorry.
-It's okay.

1147
00:47:26,810 --> 00:47:28,111
It was a bit swollen.

1148
00:47:28,178 --> 00:47:31,515
-I was happy to taste what you two made.
-Yes, it's an honor.

1149
00:47:31,582 --> 00:47:34,518
But I had to pick just one,
so I picked Fabri.

1150
00:47:35,085 --> 00:47:37,187
-<i>Grazie</i>.
-He chose what he liked.

1151
00:47:37,254 --> 00:47:38,789
Thank you.

1152
00:47:38,856 --> 00:47:41,391
-Please put the star on Chef Fabri.
-Congratulations!

1153
00:47:41,458 --> 00:47:44,361
Fabri gets his revenge!

1154
00:47:44,428 --> 00:47:47,631
-It was excellent.
-Fabri wins a star for the first time.

1155
00:47:47,698 --> 00:47:49,499
He wins against Sung-jun!

1156
00:47:49,566 --> 00:47:51,168
Congratulations!

1157
00:47:51,735 --> 00:47:54,104
LOVING (?)

1158
00:47:54,171 --> 00:47:58,675
<i>This is the second round</i>
<i>with Myung-soo's ingredients.</i>

1159
00:47:58,742 --> 00:48:01,044
This is the last return match.

1160
00:48:01,111 --> 00:48:05,282
The match is between the maniacs
of <i>Chef & My Fridge.</i>

1161
00:48:05,349 --> 00:48:08,418
-Maniacs?
-Goodness, can you say that?

1162
00:48:08,485 --> 00:48:12,489
Here's the funny thing.
Poong's first victim was Nam-no.

1163
00:48:12,556 --> 00:48:14,958
<i>-I see.</i>
-Kim Poong wins!

1164
00:48:15,926 --> 00:48:18,996
-I wanted to avoid this fight.
-Why?

1165
00:48:19,062 --> 00:48:23,667
Chef Nam-no runs a bar right now.

1166
00:48:23,734 --> 00:48:27,804
So if I fight him and win again,

1167
00:48:27,871 --> 00:48:30,374
how will he save his face?

1168
00:48:30,440 --> 00:48:32,809
He already thinks Nam-no will lose.

1169
00:48:32,876 --> 00:48:34,544
Me?

1170
00:48:34,611 --> 00:48:35,612
And you've beaten him before.

1171
00:48:35,679 --> 00:48:38,348
-Tell me about it.
-Right?

1172
00:48:38,415 --> 00:48:40,384
I wouldn't say anything if I had lost.

1173
00:48:40,450 --> 00:48:42,152
But I've won.

1174
00:48:42,219 --> 00:48:44,755
He sounds too arrogant
after just one victory.

1175
00:48:44,821 --> 00:48:47,190
I'll take him down today.

1176
00:48:47,257 --> 00:48:48,859
He's going down.

1177
00:48:48,926 --> 00:48:50,761
Look at his face. I see.

1178
00:48:50,827 --> 00:48:53,597
From what I hear, Chef Nam-no

1179
00:48:53,664 --> 00:48:56,600
can chug 5,000 cc of beer in one breath.

1180
00:48:56,667 --> 00:48:58,568
-Did you say 5,000 cc?
-The whole 5,000 cc?

1181
00:48:58,635 --> 00:49:01,838
-He said he had 5,000 heads of kimchi.
-He had 5,000 heads?

1182
00:49:01,905 --> 00:49:03,273
I do love a good drink.

1183
00:49:03,340 --> 00:49:06,276
Just like Myung-soo,
I also love to drink beer,

1184
00:49:06,343 --> 00:49:07,778
and I drink lots of it.

1185
00:49:07,844 --> 00:49:08,879
Be careful with gout.

1186
00:49:08,946 --> 00:49:11,281
You must know
what beer lovers like to eat.

1187
00:49:11,348 --> 00:49:15,652
I believe this order was made for me.

1188
00:49:15,719 --> 00:49:18,889
There's no bigger philosophy in cooking
apart from bar snacks.

1189
00:49:18,956 --> 00:49:21,358
I know I'll have an overwhelming win
after this order.

1190
00:49:21,425 --> 00:49:24,594
Also, my wine bar is
one of the best already.

1191
00:49:24,661 --> 00:49:25,862
FLEXING HIS CONFIDENCE

1192
00:49:25,929 --> 00:49:28,432
You end up feeling full
when you drink beer.

1193
00:49:28,498 --> 00:49:31,768
-That's true.
-It feels even heavier with a snack.

1194
00:49:31,835 --> 00:49:35,472
So I prefer a bar snack
that continues to make me crave beer.

1195
00:49:35,539 --> 00:49:37,774
-That's exactly what I'll make.
-I see.

1196
00:49:37,841 --> 00:49:40,811
I like it. I like that.

1197
00:49:41,645 --> 00:49:43,714
CHEF NAM-NO'S INGREDIENTS: CAVIAR, OLIVE,
CAPER, ARUGULA, RIB EYE, CHERRY TOMATO

1198
00:49:43,780 --> 00:49:45,816
TRUFFLE OLIVE SAUCE, UNCOOKED
CROISSANT DOUGH, BALSAMIC VINEGAR

1199
00:49:45,882 --> 00:49:47,017
What's it called?

1200
00:49:47,851 --> 00:49:49,586
No Beer Left Behind.

1201
00:49:51,355 --> 00:49:53,323
-No Beer Left Behind.
-No Beer Left Behind.

1202
00:49:53,390 --> 00:49:54,791
I like that name.

1203
00:49:54,858 --> 00:49:57,828
-He's a witty and neat guy.
-No Beer Left Behind.

1204
00:49:57,894 --> 00:50:00,130
-I'll make mille-feuille.
-I see.

1205
00:50:00,197 --> 00:50:04,434
Mille-feuille is actually
a type of dessert.

1206
00:50:04,501 --> 00:50:06,837
But I'll fill it with beef tartare
instead of cream.

1207
00:50:06,903 --> 00:50:11,575
I'll also serve salad
made with cherry tomatoes and arugula.

1208
00:50:11,641 --> 00:50:13,510
It'll be a light bar snack

1209
00:50:13,577 --> 00:50:16,913
that also looks pretty.

1210
00:50:17,848 --> 00:50:19,850
WEBTOON ARTIST POONG'S INGREDIENTS: TOFU,
TRUFFLE BRUSCHETTA SAUCE, MILK, CAPER

1211
00:50:19,916 --> 00:50:21,918
PEPERONCINO, CHEDDAR, CHICKEN STOCK,
FLAVORED SALT, PARSLEY, OYSTER SAUCE

1212
00:50:22,486 --> 00:50:24,054
Here's the title of my dish.

1213
00:50:25,155 --> 00:50:27,024
It's called Poong Goes On.

1214
00:50:27,090 --> 00:50:29,092
-Poong Goes On.
-It's like WIUGDC.

1215
00:50:29,159 --> 00:50:30,160
What do you mean?

1216
00:50:30,227 --> 00:50:31,661
It's short for Poong's grit goes on
even if he breaks.

1217
00:50:31,728 --> 00:50:33,630
-I see.
-Whoa.

1218
00:50:33,697 --> 00:50:34,698
Keep going even if you're broken.

1219
00:50:34,765 --> 00:50:36,266
The grit that goes on even if it breaks.

1220
00:50:36,333 --> 00:50:37,801
Yes, he got it from WIUGDC.

1221
00:50:37,868 --> 00:50:40,971
I probably have
the most losses on the show.

1222
00:50:41,038 --> 00:50:44,708
However, I'm always in good spirits.

1223
00:50:44,775 --> 00:50:47,277
-I'm that guy who keeps going.
-That's important.

1224
00:50:47,344 --> 00:50:50,013
Yes, and people who love beer

1225
00:50:50,080 --> 00:50:52,349
do not like to snack too much.

1226
00:50:52,416 --> 00:50:55,018
-You're right. I get full.
-Those who really like it.

1227
00:50:55,085 --> 00:50:58,255
-They like dried seafood,
-Yes!

1228
00:50:58,321 --> 00:51:00,323
-something they can munch on.
-Peanuts.

1229
00:51:00,390 --> 00:51:02,492
So I'll make a bar snack with tofu.

1230
00:51:02,559 --> 00:51:05,195
-What? Tofu?
-He'll make a bar snack with tofu.

1231
00:51:05,262 --> 00:51:07,464
I already have simple bar snacks.
Why would I do that?

1232
00:51:07,531 --> 00:51:09,633
Because you've had those often already.

1233
00:51:09,699 --> 00:51:12,702
-I wanted to give you a new experience.
-I see. With tofu?

1234
00:51:12,769 --> 00:51:14,838
As I watched the tofu round
on <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>,

1235
00:51:14,905 --> 00:51:17,741
I wondered what I would've done
if I were on the show.

1236
00:51:17,808 --> 00:51:19,509
I probably wouldn't have done
what they did.

1237
00:51:19,576 --> 00:51:22,345
I had a few ideas
about what I would've done there.

1238
00:51:22,412 --> 00:51:24,815
I'll make one of those ideas come true.

1239
00:51:24,881 --> 00:51:26,716
-I look forward to this.
-All right.

1240
00:51:26,783 --> 00:51:29,319
Let us begin their round.

1241
00:51:30,854 --> 00:51:32,155
I like Poong's posture.

1242
00:51:32,222 --> 00:51:35,192
-He's under the light.
-He stands directly under the light.

1243
00:51:35,258 --> 00:51:36,860
Are you standing in the rain?

1244
00:51:36,927 --> 00:51:39,529
He'll put Poong down today,
just like how he chugs down

1245
00:51:39,596 --> 00:51:41,698
a whopping 5,000 cc of beer.

1246
00:51:41,765 --> 00:51:44,067
Chef Yoon Nam-no, aka Cooking Maniac.

1247
00:51:44,134 --> 00:51:46,703
His fake lunacy
cannot win against this man.

1248
00:51:46,770 --> 00:51:48,839
He's here to give Nam-no a new nickname,

1249
00:51:48,905 --> 00:51:52,342
the chef who lost against Poong twice.

1250
00:51:52,409 --> 00:51:54,277
Webtoon Artist Poong is up.

1251
00:51:54,344 --> 00:51:57,948
Who'll be the winner
of the maniac return match?

1252
00:51:58,014 --> 00:52:01,685
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1253
00:52:03,019 --> 00:52:04,621
Begin!

1254
00:52:04,688 --> 00:52:05,922
SHOWS RESPECT!

1255
00:52:06,923 --> 00:52:08,658
A RETURN MATCH BETWEEN
THE MANIAC VS THE LUNATIC!

1256
00:52:08,725 --> 00:52:11,828
Will Poong win this match once again?

1257
00:52:13,864 --> 00:52:15,599
What did Nam-no just pull out?

1258
00:52:15,665 --> 00:52:17,934
-It's uncooked croissant dough.
-Croissant.

1259
00:52:18,001 --> 00:52:19,603
-The croissant dough.
-Croissant?

1260
00:52:19,669 --> 00:52:21,538
-He had croissant dough?
-Yes.

1261
00:52:21,605 --> 00:52:23,540
Poong is chopping the tofu.

1262
00:52:24,875 --> 00:52:28,145
We often drink beer with griddled tofu
after dipping it in soy sauce.

1263
00:52:28,211 --> 00:52:30,180
-You're right.
-He's deep-frying it.

1264
00:52:30,247 --> 00:52:32,082
I see. Fried tofu.

1265
00:52:32,149 --> 00:52:33,717
He's deep-frying tofu?

1266
00:52:33,783 --> 00:52:35,552
He'll cook it for a long time
in low temperature

1267
00:52:35,619 --> 00:52:37,320
